{"pageid": 47, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@01_geom/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@01_geom-tab7", "text": "It turns out that if we have a function from [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^m[/mathjaxinline] that we know comes from multiplication on the left with a matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], we can find this matrix by looking at where this matrix sends the standard basis vectors!  **Problem 7.1** Given [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline], there is a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline] whose associated function rotates each vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline] counterclockwise by the angle [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline]. What is it?  ![A unit circle is depicted in the left-hand image in the x y plane. The vectors 0 comma 1 and 1 comma 0 are drawn inside the circle. A unit circle is depicted in the right-hand image which shows the vectors rotated by an angle theta after applying the matrix R.](/static/images/rotation.svg)  **Solution:** The rotation maps [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} \\cos \\theta \\\\\\ \\sin \\theta \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} -\\sin \\theta \\\\\\ \\cos \\theta \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline]. We know that the matrix with columns [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{R} \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{R} \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] is the matrix we want, and that this approach for finding a matrix representing a function always works. Thus  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\textrm{first column of } \\mathbf{R})[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathbf{R} \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} \\cos \\theta \\\\\\ \\sin \\theta \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\textrm{second column of } \\mathbf{R})[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathbf{R} \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -\\sin \\theta \\\\\\ \\cos \\theta \\end{pmatrix},[/mathjaxinline] |  |      so  [mathjax]\\mathbf{R} = \\begin{pmatrix} \\cos \\theta & -\\sin \\theta \\\\\\ \\sin \\theta & \\cos \\theta \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Representing functions with matrices", "filename": "01_geom-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Representing functions with matrices"}

{"pageid": 50, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingalinearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingalinearsystems-tab10", "text": "### Testing linear dependence  To have a systematic way of testing for linear dependence, it is helpful to have a definition in terms of an algebraic relationship that we can test.  **Equivalent algebraic definition:** A collection of vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1,\\dots , \\mathbf v_n[/mathjaxinline] are **linearly dependent** if there exist scalars [mathjaxinline]c_1,\\dotsc ,c_n[/mathjaxinline] **not all zero** such that  [mathjax]c_1 \\mathbf v_1 + \\dotsb + c_n \\mathbf v_n = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ###  Proof that the two definitions are equivalent  We show that the two definitions are equivalent. First suppose that there exist scalars, not all zero, so that  [mathjax]c_1 \\mathbf v_1 + \\dotsb + c_n \\mathbf v_n = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Find the first nonzero scalar [mathjaxinline]c_i[/mathjaxinline]. Then this equation can be rewritten as  [mathjax]\\mathbf v_i = -\\frac{c_1}{c_i} \\mathbf v_1 - \\dotsb - \\frac{c_{i-1}}{c_i}\\mathbf v_{i-1}-\\frac{c_{i+1}}{c_i}\\mathbf v_{i+1} - \\dotsb - \\frac{c_n}{c_i}\\mathbf v_n,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which means that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_i[/mathjaxinline] is in the span of the the other vectors.  Now we show that the logical implication holds in the other direction as well. Note that if one of the vectors, say [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_n[/mathjaxinline], is in [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Span}\\left( \\mathbf v_1, \\dotsb , \\mathbf v_{n-1} \\right)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_n[/mathjaxinline] can be written as a linear combination of the other [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_i[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\mathbf v_n = c_1\\mathbf v_1 + c_2\\mathbf v_2 + \\dotsb + c_{n-1}\\mathbf v_{n-1}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for constants [mathjaxinline]c_1, \\dotsc , c_{n-1}[/mathjaxinline]. This is equivalent to saying that there exists a nonzero vector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} c_1 \\\\\\ c_2 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ c_{n-1} \\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] such that  [mathjax]c_1\\mathbf v_1 + c_2\\mathbf v_2 + \\dotsb + c_{n-1}\\mathbf v_{n-1} - \\mathbf v_n = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Remark 10.6** If a collection of [mathjaxinline]n-1[/mathjaxinline] vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1, \\mathbf v_2, \\dotsc , \\mathbf v_{n-1}[/mathjaxinline] are linearly independent, to test if [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1, \\dotsc , \\mathbf v_n[/mathjaxinline] are dependent, it is enough to check if [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_n[/mathjaxinline] is in the span of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1, \\mathbf v_2, \\dotsc , \\mathbf v_{n-1}[/mathjaxinline].  Why? Suppose that the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] vectors are linearly dependent. Then there is a nonzero vector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} c_1 \\\\\\ c_2 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ c_{n-1} \\\\\\ c_n \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] such that  [mathjax]c_1\\mathbf v_1 + c_2\\mathbf v_2 + \\dotsb + c_{n-1}\\mathbf v_{n-1} +c_n \\mathbf v_n = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If [mathjaxinline]c_n[/mathjaxinline] were equal to zero, this would imply that  [mathjax]c_1\\mathbf v_1 + c_2\\mathbf v_2 + \\dotsb + c_{n-1}\\mathbf v_{n-1} = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Because we assume these first [mathjaxinline]n-1[/mathjaxinline] are linearly independent, this equation is only possible if all the [mathjaxinline]c_i[/mathjaxinline] are zero. Therefore it must be the case that [mathjaxinline]c_n \\neq 0[/mathjaxinline], thus  [mathjax]\\mathbf v_n = -\\frac{c_1}{c_n}\\mathbf v_1 - \\dotsb - \\frac{c_{n-1}}{c_n}\\mathbf v_{n-1},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which means that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_n[/mathjaxinline] is in the span of the vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1, \\mathbf v_2, \\dotsc , \\mathbf v_{n-1}[/mathjaxinline].  **Example in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline]:**   Suppose we have 2 linearly independent vectors [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ -1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline]. These two vectors span a plane inside of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline]. Now suppose we have a third vector [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} a \\\\\\ b \\\\\\ c\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline]. This vector is **linearly dependent** if and only if lies in the plane spanned by the first two vectors. This is true if and only if we can write it as a linear combination of the first two vectors.  Testing linear dependence", "filename": "02_solvingalinearsystems-tab10-text2.html", "title": "Testing linear dependence"}

{"pageid": 51, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@01_geom/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@01_geom-tab7", "text": "**Geometric examples in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline]:** Here are some functions from [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline] that can be represented as a matrix: reflections across a plane through the origin, rotations about a line through the origin, and projections onto a plane or line through the origin.  **Nonexample:** A function from [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline] which translates all points by a fixed amount cannot be represented by multiplication by a matrix.  ###  (Optional) When can a function be represented by a matrix?  A matrix represents a very special kind of function called a **linear transformation** .  A function [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{f}\\, :\\, \\mathbb {R}^n \\to \\mathbb {R}^m[/mathjaxinline] is a **linear transformation** if:    **0.** it maps the zero vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline] to the zero vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^m[/mathjaxinline]: [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{f}(\\mathbf{0}) = \\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline],    **1.** for a vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] and a constant [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{f}(c\\mathbf v) = c\\mathbf{f}(\\mathbf v)[/mathjaxinline], and   **2.** for vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{w}[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{f}(\\mathbf v+ \\mathbf{w}) = \\mathbf{f}(\\mathbf v) + \\mathbf{f}(\\mathbf{w})[/mathjaxinline].  What this means roughly is that the function preserves vector addition and multiplication by a scalar. In pictures, we could draw this the following way.  ![A parallelogram with sides given by the vectors v and w has diagonal equal to the sum v plus w. A parallelogram with sides given by the vectors f of v and f of w has diagonal equal to f of v plus w.](/static/images/u4s1_lintrans_add2.svg)   If you take two vectors and add them, then take the linear transformation, this is the same   as first taking the linear transformation of each of the two vectors, and then adding them. ![The vector c v is in the same direction as v and longer by a factor of c. The vector c f of v is equal to f of c times v and is in the same direction as f of v.](/static/images/u4s1_lintrans_mult2.svg)   If you take a vector, scale it, and then take its linear transformation, this is the   same as first taking the linear transformation of the vector, and then scaling it.        Any function that is a linear transformation can be represented by a matrix by the method described above in the text.  To learn more about linear transformations, you may want to watch the following video.  [Linear transformations and matrices](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kYB8IZa5AuElist=PLZHQObOWTQDPD3MizzM2xVFitgF8hE_abindex=4)  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Canonical examples", "filename": "01_geom-tab7-text2.html", "title": "Canonical examples"}

{"pageid": 53, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@05_homog/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@05_homog-tab1", "text": "**Objectives**    * Describe systems of ODEs using linear algebra notation.     * Find a basis for the vector space of homogenous solutions in terms of eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the associated matrix.     * Express solutions to homogenous systems of ODEs in terms of a **fundamental matrix.**    * Find a **companion matrix** expressing a collection of scalar ODEs as a single system of first order ODEs.     * Find the system of ODEs that describes the dynamics of a **tuned mass damper** and **coupled oscillator.**  Objectives", "filename": "05_homog-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 54, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@05_homog/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@05_homog-tab12", "text": "Let us now look at a different system of coupled oscillator. This system is simpler than the one modelling the swaying building with the tuned mass damper inside in the sense that there is no damping, and no external force. But this system does have a third spring.  ![](/static/images/coupled-oscillator2.svg)  This system is modeled by two coupled second order constant coefficient ODEs. We will solve this [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] system of second order ODEs by first converting it to its companion system. We will find that the eigenvalues are complex and will use the usual procedure of taking the real and imaginary parts of exponential solutions to get a basis of the real solutions.  **Modeling** :    Let us model the unforced coupled oscillator.    * The extension or compression of spring 1 is given by [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline].     * The extension or compression of spring 2 is given by [mathjaxinline]x_2-x_1[/mathjaxinline].     * And the extension or compression of spring 3 is given by [mathjaxinline]-x_2[/mathjaxinline].   **Simplifying assumptions**      * We are assuming ideal springs, that is, there is no damping.       * The displacements [mathjaxinline]x_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x_2[/mathjaxinline] are small compared to the relaxed length of the middle spring. If this assumption is not satisfied, two things may happen: the masses may collide, and the spring forces may no longer be linear in the displacements.       **Force on mass 1:**   There are two spring forces acting on mass 1: the force [mathjaxinline]\\, F_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] due to spring 1 and the force [mathjaxinline]\\, F_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] due to spring 2. These are given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle F_1=-k_1x_1;[/mathjaxinline] | |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F_2=k_2(x_2-x_1).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.70)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Combining these using Newton's second law, we have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m_1 \\ddot x_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F_1+F_2[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -k_1x_1 + k_2(x_2-x_1)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -(k_1+k_2)x_1 + k_2x_2.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.71)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---           **Force on mass 2:**   Similarly, there are two forces acting on mass 2: the force [mathjaxinline]\\, F_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] from spring 2, which acts on [mathjaxinline]m_2[/mathjaxinline] with the same magnitude but opposite direction as it acts on [mathjaxinline]\\, m_1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the force [mathjaxinline]\\, F_3\\,[/mathjaxinline] from spring 3, given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle F_3=- k_3x_2.[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.72)   ---|---|---|---      Again using Newton's second law, we have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m_2 \\ddot x_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -F_2+F_3[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -k_2(x_2-x_1) - k_3x_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle k_2x_1 - (k_3+k_2)x_2.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.73)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---           **The differential equations:**   The two equations above together form a second order system:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m_1 \\ddot x_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -(k_2+k_1)x_1 + k_2x_2,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m_2 \\ddot x_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle k_2x_1 - (k_2+k_3)x_2,[/mathjaxinline] |  |      or equivalently in matrix form:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} m_1 \\ddot{x_1} \\\\\\ m_2 {\\ddot x_2}\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -(k_2+k_1)& k_2\\\\\\ k_2& \\- (k_2+k_3)\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} x_1\\\\\\ x_2\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      **Mathlet**  The coupled oscillator is simulated in the mathlet below. Adjust the values of the spring constants [mathjaxinline]\\, k_1,\\, k_2,\\, k_3\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the masses [mathjaxinline]\\, m_1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, m_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] and hit the \u201cplay\" button to see the action!  Modeling the Coupled Oscillator", "filename": "05_homog-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Modeling the Coupled Oscillator"}

{"pageid": 55, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation4_for_edx/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation4_for_edx-tab4", "text": "For your entertainment, here are proofs that the eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix are real, and that any two eigenvectors of distinct eigenvalues are orthogonal. These proofs rely on two facts about how matrix multiplication interacts with complex conjugation and transposes. Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] be two matrices, possibly with complex entries.    * [mathjaxinline](\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{B})^{T} = \\mathbf{B}^{T}\\mathbf{A}^{T}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\overline{\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{B}} = (\\overline{\\mathbf{A}})(\\overline{\\mathbf{B}})[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline](\\overline{\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{B}})^{T} = \\overline{\\mathbf{B}}^{T}\\overline{\\mathbf{A}}^{T}[/mathjaxinline]   ###  Proof that eigenvalues of a real valued symmetric matrix are real  Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{M}[/mathjaxinline] be a symmetric real valued matrix. Then in particular [mathjaxinline]\\overline{\\mathbf{M}} = \\mathbf{M}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{M}^{T} = \\mathbf{M}[/mathjaxinline].  Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] be a nonzero eigenvector of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{M}[/mathjaxinline] with eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline]. Note that the length of any vector is nonnegative, so in particular [mathjaxinline]|\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v| \\geq 0[/mathjaxinline]. Writing this in terms of matrix products we get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle |\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v|^2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\overline{(\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v)}^{T})( \\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v)[/mathjaxinline] | |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\overline{\\mathbf v}^T \\overline{\\mathbf{M}}^T)( \\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\overline{\\mathbf v}^T \\mathbf{M}^2 \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\overline{\\mathbf v}^T \\lambda ^2 \\mathbf v= \\lambda ^2 |\\mathbf v|^2[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The last line is true since if [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v= \\lambda \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{M}^2 \\mathbf v= \\mathbf{M}(\\lambda \\mathbf v) = \\lambda ^2 \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline].  Note that we now know that [mathjaxinline]|\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v|^2 = \\lambda ^2 |\\mathbf v|^2 \\geq 0[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]|\\mathbf v|^2>0[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]|\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v|^2 \\geq 0[/mathjaxinline], it follows that [mathjaxinline]\\lambda ^2\\geq 0[/mathjaxinline] as well. Therefore [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] is real.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  ###  Proof that eigenvectors corresponding to different eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix are orthogonal  Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{M}[/mathjaxinline] be a symmetric real valued matrix. (Then in particular [mathjaxinline]\\overline{\\mathbf{M}} = \\mathbf{M}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{M}^{T} = \\mathbf{M}[/mathjaxinline].)  Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] be an eigenvector of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{M}[/mathjaxinline] with eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] be an eigenvector of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{M}[/mathjaxinline] with eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline] for distinct eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline].  To show that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] are orthogonal, we will express [mathjaxinline]\\overline{\\mathbf v}_2^{T}\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] in two ways.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\overline{\\mathbf v}_2^{T}(\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v_1)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\overline{\\mathbf v}_2^{T}(\\lambda _1 \\mathbf v_1)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda _1 \\overline{\\mathbf v}_2^{T} \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Using associativity to move the parentheses on the opposite side we can also write this expression as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\overline{\\mathbf v}_2^{T}\\mathbf{M}) \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\overline{\\mathbf v}_2^{T}\\overline{\\mathbf{M}}^{T}) \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\overline{\\mathbf{M}\\mathbf v_2 })^T \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\overline{\\lambda _2 \\mathbf v_2})^{T} \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda _2 \\overline{\\mathbf v_2}^T \\mathbf v_1 \\qquad \\text{since the eigenvalues are real}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Therefore we have  [mathjax]\\lambda _1 \\overline{\\mathbf v}_2^{T} \\mathbf v_1 = \\lambda _2 \\overline{\\mathbf v}_2^{T} \\mathbf v_1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Since [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1 \\neq \\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline], this equality can only hold if [mathjaxinline]\\overline{\\mathbf v}_2^{T} \\mathbf v_1=0[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] are orthogonal. {"pageid": 56, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@8_nonlinear/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@8_nonlinear-tab1", "text": "### A simplification using torque balance  Note that the modeling of this system is much more complicated than any other system we have modeled thus far. One reason for this is the pulley which is what moves the rider along the cable. Because the mass of the pulley is negligible, the torques on the pulley must balance. What are the forces which may contribute to the torque?  ![](/static/images/zipline_diagram0.svg)  There are two tension forces [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{T}_L}}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{T}_R}}[/mathjaxinline] tangent to the outside edge of the pulley pointing along the cable to the left and right of the pulley.  If we take the origin of the pulley to be the center of the pulley, then the forces exerted on the pulley by the rider are applied to the center and do not contribute to the torque. In this model, we will ignore friction in the pulley. Thus the only two forces contributing to the torque are the two tension forces. The tension forces have different directions at the same radial distance from the center of the pulley. Thus torque balance tells us that the magnitude of these two tension forces must be equal. We write the magnitude as [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{T}}[/mathjaxinline], setting  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{T}} = |{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{T}_L}} | = |{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{T}_R}} |.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Simplification with torque balance", "filename": "8_nonlinear-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Simplification with torque balance"}

{"pageid": 57, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@04_eigenthings/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@04_eigenthings-tab14", "text": "Note that because the eigenvalues of a real symmetric matrix are always complete, a real symmetric matrix is always diagonalizable. More, it turns out, is true for symmetric matrices.  **Fun Fact 1** If [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is a symmetric, real [mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix, its eigenvalues are real.  Two vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{w}[/mathjaxinline] are **orthogonal** if their dot product is zero. The dot product of the two vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{w}[/mathjaxinline] can be written as [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v^T \\mathbf{w}[/mathjaxinline] using ordinary matrix multiplication.  **Fun Fact 2** If [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is a symmetric, real [mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix, the eigenvectors of any two distinct eigenvalues are orthogonal.  In particular, this means that we can find a basis for the eigenspaces that are all mutually orthogonal. This is because any repeated eigenvalue has a complete eigenspace, and there is an algorithm, called the Gram\u2013Schmidt algorithm, that allows us to find an orthogonal set of vectors.  Why do we care about orthogonal vectors?  Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1, \\dotsc , \\mathbf v_n[/mathjaxinline] be a collection of eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] that are pairwise orthogonal, that is  [mathjax]\\mathbf v_i^T \\mathbf v_j = 0 \\qquad \\text{if } i\\neq j.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Normalize these vectors so that each of them has length one, that is  [mathjax]\\mathbf v_i^T \\mathbf v_i =1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Once the vectors are normalized in this manner, they are said to be **orthonormal** .  Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{S}[/mathjaxinline] be the matrix whose columns are these orthonormal vectors. Then we say that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{S}[/mathjaxinline] is an **orthogonal matrix** , and has the special property that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{S}^{-1} =\\mathbf{S}^T[/mathjaxinline]. This is convenient because computing inverses is often computationally intensive, but the transpose is simple.  In particular, the diagonalization of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] can be expressed as [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}= \\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{D}\\mathbf{S}^T[/mathjaxinline].  **Remark 14.1** If you use the MATLAB command [mathjaxinline]\\texttt{[S,D] = eig(A)}[/mathjaxinline] to find the eigenvectors of a matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], the eigenvectors it finds will be unit length, and orthogonal if possible.  Symmetric matrices", "filename": "04_eigenthings-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Symmetric matrices"}

Find the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] (with multiplicity), and put them in a diagonal matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{D}[/mathjaxinline].     2. Find a basis of each eigenspace. Since [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is diagonalizable, there are [mathjaxinline]\\, n\\,[/mathjaxinline] linearly-independent eigenvectors. Substitute [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}=\\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{y}[/mathjaxinline] to get   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}\\dot{\\mathbf{y}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{y}+ \\mathbf{r}(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}\\dot{\\mathbf{y}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{D}\\mathbf{y}+ \\mathbf{r}(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{y}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathbf{D}\\mathbf{y}+ \\mathbf{S}^{-1} \\mathbf{r}(t).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      (You may skip to the last equation without performing the algebra every time.) This is a decoupled system of inhomogeneous linear ODEs.    4. Solve for each coordinate function of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{y}[/mathjaxinline].     5. Characteristic polynomial: [mathjaxinline]\\lambda ^2 - \\lambda - 2 = (\\lambda -2)(\\lambda +1)[/mathjaxinline].   Eigenvalues: [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore define  [mathjax]\\mathbf{D}= \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 2.** Calculating eigenspaces in the usual way leads to corresponding eigenvectors [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ -2 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], so define  [mathjax]\\mathbf{S}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 \\\\\\ -2 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Now [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}=\\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{D}\\mathbf{S}^{-1}[/mathjaxinline].  **Step 3.** The result of substituting [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{y}[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]\\dot{\\mathbf{y}} = \\mathbf{D}\\mathbf{y}+ \\mathbf{S}^{-1} \\mathbf{r}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}^{-1} \\mathbf{r}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{S}} \\begin{pmatrix} -1 & -1 \\\\\\ 2 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ e^{it} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\begin{pmatrix} -e^{it} \\\\\\ e^{it} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      so the decoupled system is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 2 y_1 - e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -y_2 + e^{it}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Step 4.** Solving with ERF (recall the exponential response formula ERF from the course _Introduction to differential equations_ lectures 9 and 10) gives the following particular solutions:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{-1}{i-2} e^{it} = \\left( \\frac{2}{5} + \\frac{1}{5} i \\right) e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{i+1} e^{it} = \\left( \\frac{1}{2} - {"pageid": 61, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@6_decoupling/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@6_decoupling-tab11", "text": "Recall that a matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is **diagonalizable** if it can be written as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{D}\\mathbf{S}^{-1}\\qquad \\text{where }\\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{D}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\lambda _1& & & \\\\\\ & \\lambda _2& & \\\\\\ & & \\ddots & \\\\\\ & & & \\lambda _n\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.165)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} |& |& & |\\\\\\ \\mathbf v_1& \\mathbf v_2& \\cdots & \\mathbf v_n\\\\\\ |& |& & |\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.166)      where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _i[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_i\\,[/mathjaxinline] are corresponding eigenvalue-eigenvector pairs, and the set of eigenvectors [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_1,\\, \\mathbf v_2,\\ldots ,\\, \\mathbf v_n[/mathjaxinline] are linearly independent.  Given a diagonalizable matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] the homogeneous system [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] can be decoupled as follows. First, define a new vector variable [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{y}\\,[/mathjaxinline] by the equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{y},\\, \\qquad \\text{where}\\, \\, \\mathbf{S}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} |& |& & |\\\\\\ \\mathbf v_1& \\mathbf v_2& \\cdots & \\mathbf v_n\\\\\\ |& |& & |\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.167)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Then substitute this in and rewrite the system in terms of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{y}[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}\\dot{\\mathbf{y}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{y}\\qquad (\\textrm{since } \\mathbf{S}\\, \\textrm{is a constant matrix})[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}\\dot{\\mathbf{y}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{D}\\mathbf{y}\\qquad (\\textrm{since } \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{S}=\\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{D})[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{y}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{D}\\mathbf{y}\\qquad (\\textrm{ multiply by } \\mathbf{S}^{-1} \\textrm{on the left}).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The system in terms of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{y}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is decoupled, because [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{D}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a diagonal matrix.  We can then solve for each coordinate function of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{y}[/mathjaxinline], and then compute [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{y}[/mathjaxinline].  We can view decoupling as rewriting the system in a new coordinate system in which the basis vectors are the eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{y},\\, \\qquad \\text{where}\\, \\, \\mathbf{S}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} |& |& & |\\\\\\ \\mathbf v_1& \\mathbf v_2& \\cdots & \\mathbf v_n\\\\\\ |& |& & |\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.168)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      If the eigenvalues are complex, the corresponding eigenvectors will also be complex, i.e., have complex components. All of the above remains formally true, provided we allow all the matrices to have complex entries. This means the new variables [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{u}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] will be expressed in terms of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{y}[/mathjaxinline] using complex coefficients, and the decoupled system will have complex coefficients. In most branches of science and engineering, this is perfectly acceptable, and one gets in this way a complex decoupling, and the differential equations can still be solved individually. If one insists on using real variables only, decoupling is not possible with complex eigenvalues. This is the assumption that Professor Mattuck used in the video above. {"pageid": 65, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@04_eigenthings/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@04_eigenthings-tab3", "text": "**Geometric meaning of real eigenvalues and eigenvectors**    Recall that any [mathjaxinline]n \\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] represents a function from [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n.\\,[/mathjaxinline] Therefore, an eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A},\\,[/mathjaxinline] which satisfies the equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda \\mathbf v\\qquad \\text{for some scalar } \\lambda ,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      is a vector whose image under [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a scalar multiple of itself. When the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] is real, this means that an eigenvector is a vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] whose image lies on the line in [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline] through [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline], with the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda[/mathjaxinline] as the scaling factor.  Let us revisit the examples above.  **Example 3.1** The function represented by [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 5& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 5& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& 5\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] stretches every vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]5[/mathjaxinline] times its length but does not change its direction; hence, every vector is an eigenvector associated to the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]5[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 3.2** The function represented by the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 2& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& -1\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline]    * stretches the eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] times ([mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] is the corresponding eigenvalue) its length but does not change its direction;     * collapses the eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] to the [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] vector, since [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] is the corresponding eigenvalue;     * flips the eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] across the origin to the other side of the [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline]-axis without changing its length, since [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] is the corresponding eigenvalue.   **Example 3.3** The (function represented by the) matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 0& 1\\\\\\ 1& 0\\end{pmatrix},\\,[/mathjaxinline]    * does not change the direction or length of the eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] since the corresponding eigenvalue is [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline];     * flips the eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] across the origin to the other side of the line [mathjaxinline]y=-x[/mathjaxinline], since the eigenvalue is [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline].   In each case, the image of the eigenvector lies on the same line as the eigenvector itself.      **Matrix vector mathlet**  The mathlet below shows the input and output vectors of a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] and their relationship with the eigenlines. Recall from the course _Differential equations: 2 by 2 systems_ that when the eigenvectors of an eigenvalue are all scalar mulitiples of just one eigenvector, then the line consisting of all the eigenvectors is called an **eigenline** .    To see the action of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] on its eigenvector:    1. click on all three boxes \u201cShow eigenlines,\" \u201cShow eigenvalues,\" and \u201cShow eigenvectors\";     2. choose values of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] (on the right) so that two eigenlines (green) are shown on the graph (on the left);     3. click on a point along the eigenlines (green on the graph) to select an eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf v}}[/mathjaxinline] (blue) as an input to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline];     4. observe that the output [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] (red) lies along the same line as [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf v}} ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] with the corresponding eigenvalue, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _1[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] (bottom right) as scalar factors.   Observe that when the input vector [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf v}} \\,[/mathjaxinline](blue) is **not** an eigenvector (i.e. not on an eigenline), the output [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] (red) is not on the same line as [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf v}}[/mathjaxinline].  Geometric meaning", "filename": "04_eigenthings-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Geometric meaning"}

{"pageid": 68, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@01_geom/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@01_geom-tab5", "text": "We will be using matrices throughout this course. For this reason, it is helpful to ensure that we all describe matrices and think about them in a similar way.  We will start with the novice view of a matrix as a table of numbers:  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 3 & 3 & 0 & 3\\\\\\ 3 & 47 & 3 & 9& 38 \\\\\\ 8 & 3& 0 & 0& 0\\\\\\ 0 & 0& 32 & 4 & 3 \\\\\\ 1 & 2 & 1 & 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If we do not know what these numbers are, or wish to describe a generic matrix, we may choose to use variables instead:  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} a & b & c & d & e \\\\\\ f & g & h & i & j \\\\\\ k & l & m & n& o \\\\\\ p & q & r & s & t \\\\\\ u & v & w & x & y \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      However, as our matrices get larger and larger, we tend to run out of letters pretty quickly. Instead, use a single letter and subscripts to denote its location within the matrix. We say a matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is **[mathjaxinline]m\\times n[/mathjaxinline]** if it has **[mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] rows** and **[mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] columns** . We denote the entry in the [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline]th row and [mathjaxinline]j[/mathjaxinline]th column by **[mathjaxinline]a_{ij}[/mathjaxinline]** , and write the full matrix as  [mathjax]\\begin{array}{l} \\phantom{a} \\\\\\ \\phantom{a} \\\\\\ \\phantom{a} \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{\\text{row } i}} \\\\\\ \\phantom{a} \\\\\\ \\phantom{a} \\\\\\ \\end{array} \\overset {\\qquad \\large { {\\color{blue}{\\text{column } j}} }}{ \\begin{pmatrix} a_{11} & a_{12} & \\dotsb & {\\color{blue}{|}} & \\dotsb & a_{1n} \\\\\\ a_{21} & a_{22} & \\dotsb & {\\color{blue}{|}} & \\dotsb & a_{2n} \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\dotsb & {\\color{blue}{|}} & \\dotsb & \\vdots \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{-}} & {\\color{blue}{-}} & {\\color{blue}{-}} & {\\color{blue}{a_{ij}}} & {\\color{blue}{-}} & {\\color{blue}{-}} \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\dotsb & {\\color{blue}{|}} & \\dotsb & \\vdots \\\\\\ a_{m1} & a_{m2} & \\dotsb & {\\color{blue}{|}} & \\dotsb & a_{mn} \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In this course, we will mostly be concerned with square matrices, which are matrices whose number of rows is equal to the number of columns.  We can think of multiplying vectors and matrices in 2 equivalent ways as follows:    1. To multiply [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] to get a vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{b}[/mathjaxinline], the [mathjaxinline]j[/mathjaxinline]th entry of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{b}[/mathjaxinline] is the dot product of the [mathjaxinline]j[/mathjaxinline]th row of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline].   [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} a_{11} & a_{12} & \\dotsb & a_{1n} \\\\\\ a_{21} & a_{22} & \\dotsb & a_{2n} \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\dotsb & \\vdots \\\\\\ a_{m1} & a_{m2} & \\dotsb & a_{mn} \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{x_1}} \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{x_2}} \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{x_n}} \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} a_{11}{\\color{blue}{x_1}} + a_{12}{\\color{blue}{x_2}} + \\dotsb +a_{1n}{\\color{blue}{x_n}} \\\\\\ a_{21}{\\color{blue}{x_1}} + a_{22}{\\color{blue}{x_2}} + \\dotsb +a_{2n}{\\color{blue}{x_n}} \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ a_{m1}{\\color{blue}{x_1}} + a_{m2}{\\color{blue}{x_2}} + \\dotsb + a_{mn}{\\color{blue}{x_n}} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---     2. The product [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] can be expressed as a linear combination of the columns of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]:   [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} a_{11} & a_{12} & \\dotsb & a_{1n} \\\\\\ a_{21} & a_{22} & \\dotsb & a_{2n} \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\dotsb & \\vdots \\\\\\ a_{m1} & a_{m2} & \\dotsb & a_{mn} \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{x_1}} \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{x_2}} \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{x_n}} \\end{pmatrix} = {\\color{blue}{x_1}} \\begin{pmatrix} a_{11} \\\\\\ a_{21} \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ a_{m1} \\end{pmatrix} + {\\color{blue}{x_2}} \\begin{pmatrix} a_{12} \\\\\\ a_{22} \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ a_{m2} \\end{pmatrix} + \\dotsb + {\\color{blue}{x_n}} \\begin{pmatrix} a_{1n} \\\\\\ a_{2n} \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ a_{mn} \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the coefficients are the entries of the vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline].  ### Properties of matrix vector multiplication   **0.** For any matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], and the zero vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{0} = \\mathbf{0}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **1.** For any matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], a [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] scalar, and a vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}(c\\mathbf{x}) = c(\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **2.** For any matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], and vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{y}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}(\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{y}) = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}+ \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{y}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Matrices", "filename": "01_geom-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Matrices"}

{"pageid": 70, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@01_geom/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@01_geom-tab10", "text": "**Key point of row echelon form** : Matrices in row echelon form correspond to systems that are ready to be solved immediately by **back-substitution.** To perform back-substitution, you solve for each variable in reverse order (from bottom row to top row). (On the next page, we will see that you must introduce a parameter for each variable that can not be directly expressed in terms of later variables, and substitute values into earlier equations once they are known.)  **Example problem** The augmented matrix in row echelon form  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} 1 & -1 & 4 & 1 \\\\\\ 0 & 8 & -4 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 3 & 1 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      describes a system of equations  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x - y + 4z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 8y -4z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 3z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Find the general solution to the system.  **Solution:** Solve the last equation first to get.  [mathjax]{\\color{orange}{z}} = 1/3.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Substitute this into the second to last equation to get :  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 8{\\color{orange}{y}} - 4(1/3)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{orange}{y}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1/6.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Now substitute both values into the first equation to get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{orange}{x}} - 1/6 + 4/3[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{orange}{x}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1 + 1/6 - 4/3 = -1/6 .[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Conclusion: The general solution written as a column vector is  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y \\\\\\ z \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -1/6 \\\\\\ 1/6 \\\\\\ 1/3 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Back-substitution", "filename": "01_geom-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Back-substitution"}

{"pageid": 72, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@04_eigenthings/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@04_eigenthings-tab9", "text": "Let us take a quick detour to discuss the relationship between eigenvalues and the trace and determinant of a matrix.     **Definition 9.1** The **trace** of a square matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is the sum of the entries along the main diagonal. That is, for  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{a_{11}}} & \\cdots & \\cdots & a_{1n}\\\\\\ a_{21}& {\\color{blue}{a_{22}}} & \\cdots & a_{2n}\\\\\\ \\vdots & & \\ddots & \\vdots \\\\\\ a_{n1}& \\cdots & \\cdots & {\\color{blue}{a_{nn}}} \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      the trace is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{a_{11}}} +{\\color{blue}{a_{22}}} +\\cdots +{\\color{blue}{a_{nn}}} .[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      **Example 9.2** If [mathjaxinline]A = \\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{4}} & 6 & 9 \\\\\\ 1 & {\\color{blue}{7}} & 8 \\\\\\ 2 & 3 & {\\color{blue}{5}} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{tr}A = {\\color{blue}{4}} + {\\color{blue}{7}} + {\\color{blue}{5}} = 16[/mathjaxinline].  **Warning:** Recall that trace and determinant make sense only for **square** matrices.  **Problem 9.3** For an [mathjaxinline]n \\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, A[/mathjaxinline], how do [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{tr}(-\\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}(-\\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline] relate to [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]?  ###  Solution  Negating [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] negates in particular all diagonal entries of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{tr}(-\\mathbf{A}) = -\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline].  On the other hand, negating [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] amounts to multiplying every row by [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline], which multiplies [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline](-1)^n[/mathjaxinline] because there is one factor of [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] for each row. Thus    * If [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] is even, then [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}(-\\mathbf{A}) = \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] is odd, then [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}(-\\mathbf{A}) = -\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline].   [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Trace", "filename": "04_eigenthings-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Trace"}

{"pageid": 73, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@03_fundspaces/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@03_fundspaces-tab6", "text": "### Interpreting an augmented matrix in row echelon form  Let's consider a linear system describing the intersection of two parallel planes in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x - 3y + 2z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x - 3y+2z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] |  |      This system has no solutions. Let's see what happens when we try to solve it by elimination.  The augmented matrix is  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{rrr|c} 1 & -3 & 2 & 0\\\\\\ 1 & -3 & 2 & 1 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Subtracting the first row from the second puts the matrix in row echelon form  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{rrr|c} 1 & -3 & 2 & 0\\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{1}} \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This row corresponds to the equation  [mathjax]0 x + 0 y + 0z = 1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Such an equation is never satisfied, so we say that the system is **inconsistent.** In general, when an augmented matrix has a row echelon form that has a pivot in the augmented column, the original system has no solutions.  **Example 6.3** Consider the system of equations  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_1 + 2x_2 + 2x_3 + 2x_4[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2x_1 + 4x_2 + 6x_3 + 8x_4[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_2[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 3x_1 + 6x_2 + 8x_3 + 10x_4[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_3[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 4x_1 + 8x_2 + 10x_3 + 12x_4[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_4[/mathjaxinline] |  |      (a slightly modified version of the example in the video above).  This system has augmented matrix  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cccc|c} 1 & 2 & 2 & 2 & b_1\\\\\\ 2 & 4 & 6 & 8 & b_2\\\\\\ 3 & 6 & 8 & 10 & b_3\\\\\\ 4 & 8 & 10 & 12 & b_4\\\\\\ \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The first thing that we notice is that the third row is the sum of the first and second rows. This becomes apparent when we do Gaussian elimination since the third row becomes a row of zeros.  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cccc|c} 1 & 2 & 2 & 2 & b_1\\\\\\ 2 & 4 & 6 & 8 & b_2\\\\\\ 3 & 6 & 8 & 10 & b_3\\\\\\ 4 & 8 & 10 & 12 & b_4\\\\\\ \\end{array}\\right) \\longrightarrow \\left(\\begin{array}{cccc|c} 1 & 2 & 2 & 2 & b_1\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 2 & 4 & b_2 - 2b_1\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 2 & 4 & b_3 - 3b_1\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 2 & 4 & b_4-4b_1 \\end{array}\\right)\\longrightarrow \\left(\\begin{array}{cccc|c} 1 & 2 & 2 & 2 & b_1\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 2 & 4 & b_2 - 2b_1\\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{b_3 - b_1-b_2}} \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{b_4 - 2b_1-b_2}} \\\\\\ \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The last two rows are represented by the equations  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0x_1 + 0x_2 + 0 x_3 + 0x_4[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_3-b_1-b_2[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0x_1 + 0x_2 + 0 x_3 + 0x_4[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b_4-2b_1-b_2[/mathjaxinline] |  |      In other words, this system is solvable if and only if [mathjaxinline]b_3-b_1-b_2=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b_4-2b_1-b_2=0[/mathjaxinline]. This shows us how to use our algorithm for finding solutions to linear systems to determine if a solution is solvable or not.  ###  Cool fact  There are two ways to describe a subspace of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^m[/mathjaxinline]. One is to give a basis for the subspace. The other is to describe the subspace as the set of vectors that satisfy a homogeneous linear system. Earlier we showed how to give a basis for the column space. This process of Gaussian elimination shows how to describe the column space as the set of [mathjaxinline]b_1, \\dotsc b_m[/mathjaxinline] satisfying a system of equations.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  ### Algorithm to test if a linear system is consistent (has a solution):  Consider a linear system of [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] equations in [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] variables.    1. Construct the [mathjaxinline]m \\times (n+1)[/mathjaxinline] augmented matrix.     2. Put it in row echelon form. Call this row echelon form [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline].     3. Look for a row that is all zero except for a nonzero entry in the augmented column. (Alternatively, find all of the pivots of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline], and determine if there is a pivot in the augmented column.)     4. If [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] has a row that is all zero except for an entry in the augmented column, then one of the new equations has the form   [mathjax]0 x_1 + \\cdots + 0 x_n = \\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\text{nonzero number}}} }{{\\color{orange}{b.}} }[/mathjax]|   ---|---      So the linear system is **inconsistent** . Otherwise, the system is **consistent** .  If the system is consistent, then when solving it by back substitution, the free variables correspond to the non-pivot columns, excluding the augmented column, so  [mathjax]\\\\# \\text{parameters in general solution} = \\underbrace{\\\\# \\text{non-pivot columns excluding the augmented column}}_{{\\color{blue}{\\\\# \\text{free variables}}} }.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Inhomogeneous Linear Systems: Theory and Algorithms", "filename": "03_fundspaces-tab6-text3.html", "title": "Inhomogeneous Linear Systems: Theory and Algorithms"}

{"pageid": 76, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@01_geom/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@01_geom-tab9", "text": " **Gaussian elimination** is an algorithm that specifies a sequence of equation operations guaranteed to convert a linear system into one that we can solve easily. Usually this is described in terms of row operations on an augmented matrix. It converts this matrix into what is called **row echelon form.** Here are the steps. Try reading them together with the example below.    1. Find the left-most nonzero column, and the first nonzero entry in that column (read from the top down). Call this the first **pivot.**    2. If that entry is not already in the first row, interchange its row with the first row.     3. Make all other entries of the column zero by adding suitable multiples of the first row to the others.     4. At this point, the first row is done, so ignore it, and repeat the steps above for the remaining submatrix (with one fewer row and one fewer column). In each iteration, ignore the rows already taken care of. Eventually the whole matrix will be in row echelon form.   With the algorithm, we can program a computer to solve large systems (100 equations with 100 unknowns).  **Example 9.1** Let us continue with the example from the previous page, and convert the augmented matrix to row echelon form using Gaussian elimination.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 8y - 4z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x - y + 4z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -x - 5y +2z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{c|c} \\mathbf{A}& \\mathbf{b}\\end{array}\\right) = \\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} 0 & 8 & -4 & 0 \\\\\\ 1 & -1 & 4 & 1 \\\\\\ -1 & -5 & 2 & 0 \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 1.** The leftmost nonzero column is the first one, and its first nonzero entry is the [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{1}}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} {\\color{blue}{0}} & 8 & -4 & 0 \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{1}} & -1 & 4 & 1 \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{-1}} & -5 & 2 & 0 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 2.** The [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{1}}[/mathjaxinline] is not in the first row, so interchange its row with the first row:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} {\\color{orange}{1}} & -1 & 4 & 1 \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{0}} & 8 & -4 & 0 \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{-1}} & -5 & 2 & 0 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 3.** To make all other entries of the column zero, we need to add [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] times the first row to the last row (the second row is OK already):  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} {\\color{orange}{1}} & -1 & 4 & 1 \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{0}} & 8 & -4 & 0 \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{0}} & -6 & 6 & 1 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 4.** Because entries below the pivot are all zero, the first row (in gray) is done. Start over with the submatrix that remains beneath the first row:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{-1}} & {\\color{gray}{4}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} \\\\\\ 0 & 8 & -4 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & -6 & 6 & 1 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 1.** The leftmost nonzero column is now the second column, and its first nonzero entry is the [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{8}}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{-1}} & {\\color{gray}{4}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} \\\\\\ 0 & {\\color{orange}{8}} & -4 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & -6 & 6 & 1 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 2.** The first nonzero entry is [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{8}}[/mathjaxinline], which is already in the first row of the submatrix (we are ignoring the first row of the whole matrix), so no interchange is necessary.  **Step 3.** To make all other entries below the pivot of the column zero, add [mathjaxinline]6/8[/mathjaxinline] times the (new) first row to the (new) second row:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{-1}} & {\\color{gray}{4}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} \\\\\\ 0 & {\\color{orange}{8}} & -4 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 3 & 1 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 4.** Now the first and second row of the original matrix are done (both now in gray). Start over with the submatrix beneath them:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{-1}} & {\\color{gray}{4}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} \\\\\\ {\\color{gray}{0}} & {\\color{gray}{8}} & {\\color{gray}{-4}} & {\\color{gray}{0}} \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 3 & 1 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 1.** The leftmost nonzero column is now the third column, and its first nonzero entry is the [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{3}}[/mathjaxinline] at the bottom:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{-1}} & {\\color{gray}{4}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} \\\\\\ {\\color{gray}{0}} & {\\color{gray}{8}} & {\\color{gray}{-4}} & {\\color{gray}{0}} \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{3}} & 1 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      There are no rows below this row, so we are done.  The matrix is now in **row echelon** form:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{ccc|c} {\\color{orange}{1}} & -1 & 4 & 1 \\\\\\ 0 & {\\color{orange}{8}} & -4 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{3}} & 1 \\end{array}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The first nonzero entry in each row is the **pivot.**  **Definition 9.2** A matrix is in **row echelon form** if it satisfies the following conditions:    1. All the zero rows (if any) are grouped at the bottom of the matrix.     2. The first nonzero entry in a nonzero row, which we call the **pivot,** lies farther to the right than the pivots of higher rows.     3. All entries in the column below a pivot entry are zero.   **Warning:** Some books require also that each pivot be a [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]. We are not going to require this for row echelon form, but we will require it for **reduced** row echelon form later on.  **Example 9.3** The following matrices are all in row echelon form. The pivots are highlighted in **orange.**  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{orange}{1}} & 4 & 5 \\\\\\ 0 & {\\color{orange}{3}} & 0\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{8}} \\end{pmatrix} \\qquad \\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{orange}{1}} & 4 & 5 \\\\\\ 0 & {\\color{orange}{3}} & 0\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix} \\qquad \\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{orange}{4}} & -1 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & {\\color{orange}{3}} & 2 & 1\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{4}} \\end{pmatrix} \\qquad \\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{orange}{1}} & 3 & 1 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{4}} \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Nonexamples** The following matrices are not in row echelon form.    1. The following matrix has a zero row (in blue) that is above a nonzero row.   [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 4 & 5 \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{0}} & {\\color{blue}{0}} \\\\\\ 0 & 3 & 0\\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---     2. The following matrix is not in row echelon form because the pivot in the third row is to the left of the pivot in the second row (both in blue).   [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 4 & -1 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{blue}{2}} & 1\\\\\\ 0 & {\\color{blue}{1}} & 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---     3. The following matrix is not in row echelon form because the entries below the **pivot** in the 2nd row are not all zero (highlighted in blue).   [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 3 & 1 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{4}} \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{blue}{2}} \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---    **Definition 9.4** A row echelon form of a matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is any matrix in row echelon form obtained from [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] by a sequence of row operations.  **Note:** Gaussian elimination is one algorithm for obtaining a row echelon form of a matrix. However, there are other sequences of row operations that will lead to different row echelon forms. However, all of these row echelon forms have the same solution set as the original system.  Gaussian elimination", "filename": "01_geom-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Gaussian elimination"}

{"pageid": 78, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingalinearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingalinearsystems-tab7", "text": "Here is what happens in general for homogeneous linear systems:  Recall that the set of all solutions to a homogeneous linear system [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] is called the **nullspace of matrix** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{A}}}[/mathjaxinline], and is denoted [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{NS}(\\mathbf{A})}}[/mathjaxinline].  **Theorem 7.1** If [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is a matrix, then the set of all solutions to the homogeneous linear system [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] is a vector space. (In other words if [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is an [mathjaxinline]m\\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix, then the nullspace [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{NS}(\\mathbf{A})}}[/mathjaxinline] is a subspace of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline].)   **Analogous theorem :** If [mathjaxinline]\\, P\\left(D\\right) \\,[/mathjaxinline] is a linear differential operator, then the set of solutions to the homogeneous ODE [mathjaxinline]\\, P\\left(D\\right)x=0 \\,[/mathjaxinline] is a vector space of functions. (It is a subspace of the set of all functions.)  ###  Proof of theorem  We already showed that the solutions to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] satisfy the definition of a vector space. (In fact we used this to motivate our definition of a vector space.) We replicate the proof here for completeness.  **0.** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{0} = \\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] implies that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] is in the nullspace.    **1.** If [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] is in the nullspace, this means that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}= 0[/mathjaxinline]. Then  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}(c\\mathbf{x}) = c\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}= c\\mathbf{0} = \\mathbf{0}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Thus [mathjaxinline]c\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] is also in the nullspace.    **2.** If [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}_2[/mathjaxinline] are in the nullspace, this means that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}_1 = 0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}_2 = 0[/mathjaxinline]. Then  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}(\\mathbf{x}_1+\\mathbf{x}_2) = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}_1 + \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}_2 = \\mathbf{0}+\\mathbf{0} = \\mathbf{0}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Thus [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}_1+\\mathbf{x}_2[/mathjaxinline] is also in the nullspace.
