Now, we are going to use the same idea to solve an inhomogeneous linear [mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline] **system** of ODEs:  [mathjax]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}+ \\mathbf{r},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{r}[/mathjaxinline] is a vector-valued function of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].    First, find a basis of solutions to the corresponding homogeneous system  [mathjax]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Call the basis solutions [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}_1(t),\\, \\mathbf{x}_2(t),\\, \\cdots ,\\, \\mathbf{x}_n(t).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The general homogeneous solution is any linear combination of these:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}_h(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1 \\mathbf{x}_1+\\, c_2 \\mathbf{x}_2+\\, \\cdots +\\, c_n\\mathbf{x}_n[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.131)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{X}\\mathbf{c}\\qquad \\text{where } \\, \\mathbf{X}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} |& |& & |\\\\\\ \\mathbf{x}_1& \\mathbf{x}_2& \\cdots & \\mathbf{x}_n\\\\\\ |& |& & |\\end{pmatrix},\\, \\, \\mathbf{c}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} c_1\\\\\\ c_2\\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ c_n\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.132)      Notice that in 1 dimension, [mathjaxinline]x_h(t)=c x_1(t)=x_1(t)c,\\,[/mathjaxinline] but in higher dimensions, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}_h(t)=\\mathbf{X}\\mathbf{c}[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{c}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a column vector and must be placed to the right of the fundamental matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{X}[/mathjaxinline].    To find a particular solution, we let the coefficients [mathjaxinline]c_i[/mathjaxinline] vary with time. In other words, replace the constant vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{c}\\,[/mathjaxinline] by the vector **function**  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf v(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} v_1(t)\\\\\\ v_2(t)\\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ v_n(t)\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.133)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Now, substitute [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}=\\mathbf{X}\\mathbf v(t)[/mathjaxinline] in the original system:  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}+ \\mathbf{r}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{X}} \\mathbf v+ \\mathbf{X}\\dot{\\mathbf v}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{X}\\mathbf v+ \\mathbf{r}\\qquad (\\text{product rule of differentiation})[/mathjaxinline] | |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{X}\\mathbf v+ \\mathbf{X}\\dot{\\mathbf v}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{X}\\mathbf v+ \\mathbf{r}\\qquad (\\dot{\\mathbf{X}}\\, =\\, \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{X})[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{X}\\dot{\\mathbf v}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{r}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf v}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{X}^{-1} \\mathbf{r}\\qquad (\\mathbf{X}\\, \\, \\text{invertible}).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      This means  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf v(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\mathbf{X}^{-1} \\mathbf{r}\\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.134)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      and the general solution to the inhomogeneous system is  [mathjax]\\mathbf{x}(t)=\\mathbf{X}\\mathbf v(t)\\, =\\, \\mathbf{X}\\left(\\int \\mathbf{X}^{-1} \\mathbf{r}\\, dt\\right),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for any fundamental matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{X}\\,[/mathjaxinline] of the associated homogeneous This is a family of solutions because the indefinite integral on the right hand side will result in a constant of integration. Note that the constant of integration is a column vector. {"pageid": 117, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@03_fundspaces/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@03_fundspaces-tab7", "text": "**Question 7.1**  Choose a value of [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] for which the system is inconsistent, and another value of [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] for which the system is consistent and has infinitely many solutions. What are two of those solutions?  [mathjax]\\begin{cases} 3x + 2y = 10 \\\\\\ 6x + 4y = b. \\end{cases}[/mathjax]| (3.1)   ---|---      ###  Worked Solution  We put the system into augmented matrix form: [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cc|c} 3 & 2 & 10 \\\\\\ 6 & 4 & b \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]| (3.2)   ---|---   We can eliminate the second equation by subtracting [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] times the first equation from it, leaving us with [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cc|c} 3 & 2 & 10 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & b-20 \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]| (3.3)   ---|---   The second row reads [mathjaxinline]0\\cdot x + 0\\cdot y =b-20[/mathjaxinline]. If [mathjaxinline]b\\neq 20[/mathjaxinline], then the equation can never be satisfied, in which case, there would be no solutions to the system. If [mathjaxinline]b=20[/mathjaxinline], then there are infinitely many solutions to the system. The first row tells us that [mathjax]3x + 2y = 10,[/mathjax]| (3.4)   ---|---   or that [mathjax]x+\\frac{2}{3} y = \\frac{10}{3}.[/mathjax]| (3.5)   ---|---   Setting [mathjaxinline]y = c_{1}[/mathjaxinline] we see that [mathjax]x = \\frac{10}{3} - \\frac{2}{3} c_{1},[/mathjax]| (3.6)   ---|---   so [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} x \\\\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 10/3 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix} + c_{1} \\begin{pmatrix} -2/3 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]| (3.7)   ---|---   You should check to see if the two solutions you found can be written in this form. To get any one solution plug in a specific number for [mathjaxinline]c_{1}[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 118, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@forum/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@forum-tab1", "text": "The discussion forum is the tool for connecting with the community of online learners in this course. {"pageid": 119, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@03_fundspaces/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@03_fundspaces-tab4", "text": "**Theorem 4.3** For any [mathjaxinline]m \\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\boxed { \\mathrm{nullity}(\\mathbf{A}) + \\mathrm{rank}(\\mathbf{A}) = n. }[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This theorem is called the **rank-nullity theorem** .  ### Proof  Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] be a row echelon form of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{nullity}(\\mathbf{A}) + \\mathrm{rank}(\\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dim \\mathrm{NS}(\\mathbf{A}) + \\dim \\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline] | |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\\\# \\, \\, \\text{non-pivot columns of } \\mathbf{B}) + (\\\\# \\, \\, \\text{pivot columns of } \\mathbf{B})[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\\\# \\, \\, \\text{columns of } \\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle n.[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Rank nullity theorem", "filename": "03_fundspaces-tab4-text2.html", "title": "Rank nullity theorem"}

{"pageid": 121, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@04_eigenthings/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@04_eigenthings-tab2", "text": "In the course _Differential equations: 2 by 2 systems_ , we learned that the first step in solving a linear [mathjaxinline]\\, 2 \\times 2 \\,[/mathjaxinline] system of differential equations, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x},\\,[/mathjaxinline] is to find the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]. The procedure for solving linear [mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline] systems of DEs is the same, and starts with finding eigenvalues and eigenvectors. And even outside the context of differential equations, the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a matrix tell us a lot about what the matrix does as a function on [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline].  **Definition 2.1** Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] be an [mathjaxinline]n \\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix.    * An **eigenvalue of** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{A}}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] is a **scalar** [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda \\,[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v= \\lambda \\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] for some **nonzero** vector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline].     * An **eigenvector of** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{A}}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **associated with an eigenvalue** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\lambda }} \\,[/mathjaxinline] is a **nonzero** vector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v= \\lambda \\mathbf v.[/mathjaxinline]   (We also say that an eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] \u201ccorresponds to,\" or \u201cbelongs to\" an eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline].)  The eigenvalue-eigenvector problem is to find all possible scalars [mathjaxinline]\\lambda ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and for each [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] all vectors [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] such that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v= \\lambda \\mathbf v.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      **Warning:** Eigenvalues and eigenvectors are defined only for **square** matrices.    **Warning:** The zero vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] is never an eigenvector.   **Note:** Everyone allows that [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =0[/mathjaxinline] can be an eigenvalue.  **Example 2.2** The matrix [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 5& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 5& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& 5\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] satisfies  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\, \\begin{pmatrix} 5& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 5& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& 5\\end{pmatrix}\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 5 \\mathbf v\\qquad \\text{for all }\\, \\mathbf v\\, \\text{in }\\, \\mathbb {R}^3.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Therefore, the number [mathjaxinline]5[/mathjaxinline] is an eigenvalue and all (nonzero) vectors in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline] are eigenvectors associated to the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]5[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 2.3** The diagonal matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 2& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& -1\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] satisfies the following:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 2& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& -1\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 2& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& -1\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}\\, =\\, 0\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 2& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& -1\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -1\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The first equation above shows that the scalar [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] is an eigenvalue with associated eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline]. Similarly, the second and third equations show that [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] are both eigenvalues, and [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] are eigenvectors associated to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] respectively.  **Example 2.4** The matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 0& 1\\\\\\ 1& 0\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] satisfies  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0& 1\\\\\\ 1& 0\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0& 1\\\\\\ 1& 0\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}\\, =\\, (-1)\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -1\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Therefore, the scalar [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] is an eigenvalue with an associated eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix},\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] is an eigenvalue with an associated eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -1\\end{pmatrix}.\\,[/mathjaxinline]  The eigenvalue-eigenvector problem", "filename": "04_eigenthings-tab2-text1.html", "title": "The eigenvalue-eigenvector problem"}

{"pageid": 122, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingalinearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingalinearsystems-tab5", "text": "### The geometry of vectors  Our ability to visualize vectors in dimensions larger than [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] limits our ability to draw images. But we continue to use our geometric intuition in lower dimensions to inform our algebraic treatment of higher dimensional vectors.  **In [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline] a vector has 2 entries.**| **In [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline] a vector has 3 entries.**| **In [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^N[/mathjaxinline] a vector has [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline] entries.**   ---|---|---   Example: [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} -2\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline]. |  Example: [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ -3 \\\\\\ 8 \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline]. |  Example: [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\\\\\ a_2 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ a_N \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].   ![Arrow starting at the origin and ending at the coordinate negative 2 comma 1.](/static/images/vectorR2.svg)| ![Arrow starting at the origin and ending at the coordinate 1 comma negative 3 comma 8.](/static/images/vectorR3.svg)|      A video refresher if needed: [Vectors, what are they?](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fNk_zzaMoSslist=PLZHQObOWTQDPD3MizzM2xVFitgF8hE_abindex=2)  The geometry of vectors", "filename": "02_solvingalinearsystems-tab5-text1.html", "title": "The geometry of vectors"}

{"pageid": 123, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@03_fundspaces/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@03_fundspaces-tab14", "text": "Even for large matrices, we can easily compute determinants in special cases (such as for diagonal and upper triangular matrices). We record some properties of determinants that will help us compute determinants more easily.  The **diagonal** of a matrix consists of the entries [mathjaxinline]a_{ij}[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]i=j[/mathjaxinline].  A **diagonal matrix** is a square matrix that has zeros everywhere outside the diagonal:  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{a_{11}}} & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & {\\color{blue}{a_{22}}} & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{blue}{a_{33}}} \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (it may have some zeros along the diagonal too).  An **upper triangular matrix** is a matrix whose entries strictly below the diagonal are all [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{a_{11}}} & a_{12} & a_{13} \\\\\\ 0 & {\\color{blue}{a_{22}}} & a_{23} \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{blue}{a_{33}}} \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (the entries on or above the diagonal may or may not be [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]).  **Example 14.1** Any square matrix in row-echelon form is upper triangular.  **Theorem 14.2** The determinant of an upper triangular matrix equals the product of the diagonal entries.  For example,  [mathjax]\\mathrm{det}\\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{a_{11}}} & a_{12} & a_{13} \\\\\\ 0 & {\\color{blue}{a_{22}}} & a_{23} \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{blue}{a_{33}}} \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix} = {\\color{blue}{a_{11} \\, a_{22} \\, a_{33}}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---   Why is the theorem true? The Laplace expansion along the first column shows that the determinant is [mathjaxinline]a_{11}[/mathjaxinline] times a upper triangular minor with diagonal entries [mathjaxinline]a_{22},\\ldots ,a_{nn}[/mathjaxinline].  Diagonal Matrices", "filename": "03_fundspaces-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Diagonal Matrices"}

{"pageid": 126, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@01_geom/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@01_geom-tab2", "text": "### Review of solving 2x2 systems of DEs  Given a system of differential equations, our first step is to write this system as a matrix system  [mathjax]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}+ \\mathbf{b}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      For now, we assume [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{b}= 0[/mathjaxinline], as we will not handle solving the inhomogeneous case until we've developed tools from linear algebra to help us in this endeavor.  The process for solving the system [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = A \\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] which has distinct eigenvalues is as follows:        **Step 1:** Find the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline]. (Find [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1, \\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline] that solves [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}(A-\\lambda I) = 0[/mathjaxinline].)    **Step 2:** Find the eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] corresponding to each eigenvalue. (Find [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1,\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] that solve [mathjaxinline](A-\\lambda _i I)\\mathbf v= 0[/mathjaxinline] for each [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _i[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]i=1,2[/mathjaxinline].)    **Step 3:** Solutions take the form  [mathjax]\\mathbf{x}(t) = c_1 e^{\\lambda _1 t} \\mathbf v_1+c_2 e^{\\lambda _2 t} \\mathbf v_2[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for arbitrary constants [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline] which can be determined from initial conditions.  The process of solving homogenous higher order systems of differential equations consists of the same steps if there are distinct eigenvalues. The key issues are that we must now expand our linear algebra toolbox to handle solutions to linear systems, linear independence, determinants, eigenvalues and eigenvectors, and more in 3 or more dimensions. We will also be able to use these tools to solve systems with repeated eigenvalues. That is the goal of the next several lectures.  We will develop our linear algebra toolbox both by hand on paper and with computer aid MATLAB in tandem.  Review", "filename": "01_geom-tab2-text2.html", "title": "Review"}

{"pageid": 127, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@03_fundspaces/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@03_fundspaces-tab10", "text": "Suppose that we have two functions from [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline]. The first rotates all points 90 degrees counter clockwise about the origin. The second reflects across the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis. Both of these functions can be represented by a matrix.  90 degree rotation counterclockwise: |  |  Reflection across [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis:   ---|---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix} \\longrightarrow \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix} \\longrightarrow \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} \\longrightarrow \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} \\longrightarrow \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ -1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1\\\\\\ 1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline]   ![Smiley face centered at the origin is rotated 90 degrees counterclockwise.](/static/images/pirate_smiley_rotate.svg)|  | ![Smiley face centered at the origin is reflected across the x axis.](/static/images/pirate_smiley_reflect.svg)      We can compose these two functions, first rotating 90 degrees counterclockwise, and then reflecting across the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis.  ![Smiley face centered at the origin is rotated 90 degrees counterclockwise and then reflected across the x axis.](/static/images/pirate_smiley_rotate_reflect.svg)  But what matrix represents this composed function? One way is to figure it out by seeing where each of the standard basis vectors is sent by the composition.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & -1 \\end{pmatrix} \\left[\\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1\\\\\\ 1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}\\right][/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & -1 \\end{pmatrix} \\left[ \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1\\\\\\ 1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} \\right][/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Therefore the matrix representing the composed matrix is  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1 \\\\\\ -1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      There is an easier way to figure out what the composed matrix is in terms of the original two matrices. And that's the matrix product.  ### Defining the matrix product  Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is an [mathjaxinline]m\\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix, and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] is an [mathjaxinline]n\\times p[/mathjaxinline] matrix. Starting with a vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^p[/mathjaxinline], applying left multiplication by the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] gives a vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline]. Then applying left multiplication by [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] gives a vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^m[/mathjaxinline]. This composition of functions defines a new function sending the vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}(\\mathbf{B}\\mathbf v)[/mathjaxinline].  ![See text above.](/static/images/composition_matrixmult.png)      This composition function itself can be viewed as left multiplication by some matrix. What is it? The answer is called the matrix product [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline]. The matrix product [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] is characterized by the property  [mathjax](\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{B}) \\mathbf v= \\mathbf{A}(\\mathbf{B}\\mathbf v) \\qquad \\text{for all vectors } \\mathbf v\\text{ in } \\mathbb {R}^p.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The matrix product [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] is defined if and only if the number of columns of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is equal to the number of rows of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline].  Composition and matrix multiplication", "filename": "03_fundspaces-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Composition and matrix multiplication"}

{"pageid": 129, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@01_geom/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@01_geom-tab11", "text": "**Goal:** After writing the system as an augmented matrix, apply Gaussian elimination to put the augmented matrix into row echelon form, and then use back substitution to solve the system.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 6z+2u-4v-8w[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 8[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.7)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 3z+u-2v-4w[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 4[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.8)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2x-3y+z+4u-7v+w[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.9)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 6x-9y+11u-19v+3w[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.10)       **Solution:** Start by writing the system as an augmented matrix.  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cccccc|c} 0 & 0 & 6 & 2 & -4 & -8 & 8 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 3 & 1 & -2 & -4 & 4 \\\\\\ 2 & -3 & 1 & 4 & -7 & 1 & 2 \\\\\\ 6 & -9 & 0 & 11 & -19 & 3 & 0 \\\\\\ \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Next we apply the steps of Gaussian elimination. **Step 1.** The leftmost nonzero column is the first one, and its first nonzero entry is the [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{2}}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cccccc|c} {\\color{orange}{0}} & 0 & 6 & 2 & -4 & -8 & 8 \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{0}} & 0 & 3 & 1 & -2 & -4 & 4 \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{2}} & -3 & 1 & 4 & -7 & 1 & 2 \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{6}} & -9 & 0 & 11 & -19 & 3 & 0 \\\\\\ \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 2.** The [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{2}}[/mathjaxinline] is not in the first row, so interchange its row with the first row:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cccccc|c} {\\color{orange}{2}} & -3 & 1 & 4 & -7 & 1 & 2 \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{0}} & 0 & 3 & 1 & -2 & -4 & 4 \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{0}} & 0 & 6 & 2 & -4 & -8 & 8 \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{6}} & -9 & 0 & 11 & -19 & 3 & 0 \\\\\\ \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 3.** To make all other entries of the column zero, we need to subtract [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] times the first row from the last row (the second and third rows are OK already):  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cccccc|c} {\\color{orange}{2}} & -3 & 1 & 4 & -7 & 1 & 2 \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{0}} & 0 & 3 & 1 & -2 & -4 & 4 \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{0}} & 0 & 6 & 2 & -4 & -8 & 8 \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{0}} & 0 & -3 & -1 & 2 & 0 & -6 \\\\\\ \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 4.** Because entries below the pivot are all zero, the first row (in gray) is done. Start over with the submatrix that remains beneath the first row:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cccccc|c} {\\color{gray}{2}} & {\\color{gray}{-3}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{4}} & {\\color{gray}{-7}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{2}} \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 3 & 1 & -2 & -4 & 4 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 6 & 2 & -4 & -8 & 8 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & -3 & -1 & 2 & 0 & -6 \\\\\\ \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 1.** The leftmost nonzero column is now the third column, and its first nonzero entry is the [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{3}}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cccccc|c} {\\color{gray}{2}} & {\\color{gray}{-3}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{4}} & {\\color{gray}{-7}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{2}} \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{3}} & 1 & -2 & -4 & 4 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{6}} & 2 & -4 & -8 & 8 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{-3}} & -1 & 2 & 0 & -6 \\\\\\ \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 2.** The first nonzero entry is [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{3}}[/mathjaxinline], which is already in the first row of the submatrix (we are ignoring the first row of the whole matrix), so no interchange is necessary.  **Step 3.** To make all other entries below the pivot of the column zero, subtract [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] times the (new) first row to the (new) second row, and add the (new) first row to the (new) third row:  [mathjax]\\left(\\begin{array}{cccccc|c} {\\color{gray}{2}} & {\\color{gray}{-3}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{4}} & {\\color{gray}{-7}} & {\\color{gray}{1}} & {\\color{gray}{2}} \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{3}} & 1 & -2 & -4 & 4 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{0}} & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & {\\color{orange}{0}} & 0 & 0 & -4 & -2 \\\\\\ \\end{array}\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 4.** Now the first and second row of the original matrix are done (both now in gray). {"pageid": 130, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingalinearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingalinearsystems-tab4", "text": "Consider the vector space [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline]. This is a 3 dimensional vector space. If we have one equation, [mathjaxinline]ax+by+cz=0[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] are not all zeros, then the solutions to this equation describe a plane through the origin. Therefore the dimension of the solution space is 2, which is one less than all possible vectors in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline]. If we add a second equation what happens?  When we add a second equation, the dimension of the solution space can at most decrease by [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] again. However, if the second equation describes the same plane as the first equation, the solution set remains unchanged!  **Principle:** Each additional equation (of the form [mathjaxinline]ax +by + cz=0[/mathjaxinline]) reduces the dimension of the solution space by at most [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] equations reduces the dimension of the solution space by at most [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline].  If our [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] equations have [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] variables, then we started with the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] dimensional space [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline]. The smallest possible dimension of the solution space is [mathjaxinline]n-m[/mathjaxinline]. This suggests that for a general system with [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] equations in [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] variables, the dimension of the solution space is at most [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] and at least [mathjaxinline]n-m[/mathjaxinline] since each equation cuts the dimension of the solution space by at most [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline].  Reformulated in terms of matrices, this says that for an [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], the solution space to the homogeneous equation [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] can be at most be [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] dimensional, and at least [mathjaxinline]n-m[/mathjaxinline] dimensional. By the end of this lecture, we'll make what we mean by [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] dimensions more precise, and we will have an algorithm for determining the dimension of the solutions to any homogeneous system.  Homogeneous linear systems", "filename": "02_solvingalinearsystems-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Homogeneous linear systems"}

{"pageid": 132, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@6_decoupling/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@6_decoupling-tab8", "text": "Consider a thermally insulated metal bar with the left and right ends fixed at the temperatures [mathjaxinline]x_L\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, x_R[/mathjaxinline] (in [mathjaxinline]\\text{degrees Celsius}[/mathjaxinline]) respectively. (To maintain the temperatures at the end points, one has to connect the ends to heating or cooling sources.) We are interested in how heat flows through the rod.  ![](/static/images/u5s2_heatedbar-v2.svg)  To start, assume that the bar is 30 centimeters long and install a thermometer every 10 centimeters. Hence two temperatures [mathjaxinline]x_1=x_1(t)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]x_2=x_2(t)[/mathjaxinline] (in [mathjaxinline]\\text{degrees Celsius}[/mathjaxinline]) are recorded as time passes.    What we have done is simplify the model for the temperature along the bar to a discrete model that tracks the temperatures at only two locations.    Newton's law of cooling says that the rate of change of temperature is proportional to the difference in temperatures. The rate of change of the temperature [mathjaxinline]\\, x_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] is affected by the temperatures [mathjaxinline]\\, x_L\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, x_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] at the adjacent sites. The contribution to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\frac{dx_1}{dt} \\,[/mathjaxinline] from the left is [mathjaxinline]\\, k(x_L-x_1)\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is a positive constant (with dimension [mathjaxinline]\\text{time}^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]). Note that if [mathjaxinline]x_L>x_1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]\\, k(x_L- x_1)>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and heat flows from the left end of the bar towards the measuring site of [mathjaxinline]x_1.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]   Similarly, the contribution to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\frac{dx_1}{dt} \\,[/mathjaxinline] from the right is [mathjaxinline]\\, k(x_2-x_1).\\,[/mathjaxinline] Note that we have used the same constant [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] because we assume the metal bar has the same conductivity and that the location of [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] is equidistant from [mathjaxinline]\\, x_L\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, x_2[/mathjaxinline]. The equation for [mathjaxinline]\\, \\frac{dx_1}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] is therefore  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dx_1}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad k(x_L-x_1) + k(x_2-x_1) = k(x_L - 2x_1 + x_2).[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---      By the same reasoning, the equation for [mathjaxinline]\\, \\frac{dx_2}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d x_2}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad k(x_1-x_2) + k(x_R-x_2) = k(x_1 - 2x_2 + x_R).[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---      For simplicity, let [mathjaxinline]k=1[/mathjaxinline]. In matrix form, the [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] inhomogeneous system is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{r}\\qquad \\text{where }\\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\\\\\ x_2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -2 & 1 \\\\\\ 1 & -2 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{r}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} x_L \\\\\\ x_R\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Example: decoupling the heated rod", "filename": "6_decoupling-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Example: decoupling the heated rod"}

{"pageid": 133, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@04_eigenthings/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@04_eigenthings-tab13", "text": "Suppose that [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix with a basis of eigenvectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1,\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] corresponding to the distinct eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1,\\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline] respectively (i.e. [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is complete).     **Warning :** For what we are about to do, the eigenvectors must be listed in the same order as their eigenvalues.  Use the eigenvalues to define a diagonal matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{D}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\mathbf{D}= \\begin{pmatrix} \\lambda _1 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & \\lambda _2 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The matrix mapping [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1,\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline], respectively, is the matrix  [mathjax]\\mathbf{S}= \\begin{pmatrix} |& |\\\\\\ \\mathbf v_1 & \\mathbf v_2 \\\\\\ |& |\\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      whose columns are the eigenvectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1,\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline].  **Question 13.1** What is the [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix that maps [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1 \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2 \\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline], respectively?  The picture below illustrates two ways of getting [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1 \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2 \\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] out of [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] respectively. Based on that image, construct two matrices that answer the question.  ![Four images are shown. The top left image shows the vectors 0 comma 1 and 1 comma 0. Starting from the top left image and applying the matrix D leads to the top right image which shows the vectors 0 comma lambda sub 2 and lambda sub 1 comma 0. Applying the matrix S leads to the bottom right image which shows the vectors lambda sub 2 times v sub 2 and lambda sub 1 times v sub 1. Restarting from the top left image and applying the matrix S leads to the bottom left image which shows the vectors v sub 2 and v sub 1. Then applying the matrix A leads to the bottom right image which shows the vectors lambda sub 2 times v sub 2 and lambda sub 1 times v sub 1.](/static/images/diagonalization.svg)  ###  Answer 1  [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{S}[/mathjaxinline], because applying [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{S}[/mathjaxinline] means that [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] are mapped by [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{S}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1,\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline], which are then mapped by [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1 \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2 \\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  ###  Answer 2  [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{D}[/mathjaxinline], because [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] are mapped by [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{D}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} \\lambda _1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ \\lambda _2 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] which are then mapped by [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{S}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1 \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2 \\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Conclusion:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{S}=\\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{D}[/mathjaxinline].   ( _Memory aid:_ Just as in the eigenvalue-eigenvector equation [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v=\\lambda \\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is applied to an eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v,\\,[/mathjaxinline] here [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] should be applied to the matrix whose columns are the eigenvectors, hence [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{S}[/mathjaxinline].)  Multiply by [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{S}^{-1}[/mathjaxinline] on the right to get another way to write it:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{S}\\mathbf{D}\\mathbf{S}^{-1}\\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\mathbf{S}= \\begin{pmatrix} |& |\\\\\\ \\mathbf v_1 & \\mathbf v_2 \\\\\\ |& |\\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.32)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Writing the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] like this is called **diagonalizing** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline].     **Remark:**. We can think of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{S}= \\begin{pmatrix} \\mathbf v_1 & \\mathbf v_2 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] as a \u201ccoordinate-change matrix\" or \u201cchange-of-basis matrix\" that    * relates the standard basis [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] to the basis of eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], and     * relates the easy matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{D}[/mathjaxinline] scaling the standard basis vectors to the original matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] scaling the original eigenvectors. {"pageid": 134, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@03_fundspaces/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@03_fundspaces-tab10", "text": "### Matrix multiplication  Let us illustrate matrix multiplication with an example.  **Example 10.1** Multiply a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 3[/mathjaxinline] matrix by a [mathjaxinline]3 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] a matrix:  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{2}} & {\\color{blue}{4}} & {\\color{blue}{1}} \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{-3}} & {\\color{orange}{5}} & {\\color{orange}{-1}} \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} x& u \\\\\\ y & v\\\\\\ z & w \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{2}} x+{\\color{blue}{4}} y +{\\color{blue}{1}} z & {\\color{blue}{2}} u+{\\color{blue}{4}} v +{\\color{blue}{1}} w \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{-3}} x +{\\color{orange}{5}} y-{\\color{orange}{1}} z & {\\color{orange}{-3}} u +{\\color{orange}{5}} v-{\\color{orange}{1}} w \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The product is a [mathjaxinline]\\, 2 \\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] matrix. The **[mathjaxinline]i,j[/mathjaxinline]-entry** of a matrix is the entry in the [mathjaxinline]\\, i[/mathjaxinline]th row and [mathjaxinline]\\, j[/mathjaxinline]th column of the matrix.    Consider two matrices  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} a_{11} & a_{12} & \\dotsb & & \\dotsb & a_{1n} \\\\\\ a_{21} & a_{22} & \\dotsb & & \\dotsb & a_{2n} \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & & & \\vdots \\\\\\ & & & {\\color{blue}{a_{ij}}} & & \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & & & \\ddots & \\vdots \\\\\\ a_{m1} & a_{m2} & \\dotsb & & \\dotsb & a_{mn} \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix} \\qquad \\qquad \\mathbf{B}= \\begin{pmatrix} b_{11} & b_{12} & \\dotsb & & \\dotsb & b_{1p} \\\\\\ b_{21} & b_{22} & \\dotsb & & \\dotsb & b_{2p} \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & & & \\vdots \\\\\\ & & & {\\color{blue}{b_{ij}}} & & \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & & & \\ddots & \\vdots \\\\\\ b_{n1} & b_{n2} & \\dotsb & & \\dotsb & b_{np} \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The [mathjaxinline]i,j[/mathjaxinline]-entry of the product [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] is the dot product of the [mathjaxinline]\\, i[/mathjaxinline]th row of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] and the [mathjaxinline]\\, j[/mathjaxinline]th column of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline]. For example, the entry in the third row and second column of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{C}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] is the product of the third row of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] and the second column of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]c_{32} = \\begin{pmatrix} a_{31} & a_{32} & \\dotsb & a_{3n}\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} b_{12} \\\\\\ b_{22} \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ b_{n2} \\end{pmatrix} = a_{31}b_{12} + a_{32}b_{22} + \\dotsb + a_{3n}b_{n2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ### Another perspective:  We can also compute the matrix product one column at a time. Multiplying [mathjaxinline]\\; \\mathbf{A}\\;[/mathjaxinline] by (the [mathjaxinline]j[/mathjaxinline]th column of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{B}\\,[/mathjaxinline]) gives (the [mathjaxinline]j[/mathjaxinline]th column of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{C}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{B}\\,[/mathjaxinline]).  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}(\\text{the $j$th column of }\\mathbf{B}) = \\text{the $j$th column of } \\mathbf{C}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This shows that each column of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{C}[/mathjaxinline] is a linear combination of the columns of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]. The coefficients of that linear combination are the entries in the the corresponding column of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline].  Computing matrix products", "filename": "03_fundspaces-tab10-text2.html", "title": "Computing matrix products"}

{"pageid": 140, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@05_homog/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@05_homog-tab5", "text": "**Problem 5.1** Find the general solution [mathjaxinline](x(t),y(t),z(t))[/mathjaxinline] to the system  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2 x[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -6 x + 8 y + 3 z[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{z}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 18 x - 18 y - 7 z.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      ###  Solution:  In matrix form, this is [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ -6 & 8 & 3 \\\\\\ 18 & -18 & -7\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].  **Step 1. Find the eigenvalues.** To do this, compute  [mathjax]\\mathrm{det}(\\lambda \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}) = \\begin{vmatrix} \\lambda -2 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 6 & \\lambda -8 & -3 \\\\\\ -18 & 18 & \\lambda + 7 \\end{vmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Use Laplace expansion along the first row to get  [mathjax](\\lambda -2) \\bigl ((\\lambda -8)(\\lambda +7) - 18(-3) \\bigr )= (\\lambda -2)(\\lambda ^2-\\lambda -2) = (\\lambda -2)(\\lambda -2)(\\lambda +1),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so the eigenvalues are **[mathjaxinline]2,2,-1[/mathjaxinline]** .  **Step 2. Find a basis of each eigenspace and write down the exponential solutions.**   **Eigenspace of** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda =2}}[/mathjaxinline] **:** This is the nullspace of  [mathjax]2\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 6 & -6 & -3 \\\\\\ -18 & 18 & 9 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Converting to row-echelon form gives  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 6 & -6 & -3 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which corresponds to the single equation  [mathjax]-6x+6y+3z=0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Solve by back-substitution: [mathjaxinline]z=c_1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]y=c_2[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]x=y+z/2 = c_2 +c_1/2[/mathjaxinline], so  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} x \\\\\\ y \\\\\\ z \\end{pmatrix} = c_1 \\begin{pmatrix} 1/2 \\\\\\ 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} + c_2 \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1/2 \\\\\\ 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] form a basis for the eigenspace at [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]. (We were lucky here that the number of basis eigenvectors is as large as the multiplicity of the eigenvalue, so that the eigenspace of [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] was not deficient.)    The exponential solutions built from these eigenvectors are:  [mathjax]e^{2t} \\begin{pmatrix} 1/2 \\\\\\ 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}, \\quad e^{2t} \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Eigenspace of** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda =-1}}[/mathjaxinline] **:** This is the nullspace of  [mathjax]-\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} -3 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 6 & -9 & -3 \\\\\\ -18 & 18 & 6 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Converting to row-echelon form gives  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 3 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & -9 & \\- 3 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which corresponds to the system  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 3x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 9y+3z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Back-substitution leads to  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} x \\\\\\ y \\\\\\ z \\end{pmatrix} = c \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ -1 \\\\\\ 3 \\end{pmatrix},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ -1 \\\\\\ 3 \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline] by itself is a basis for the eigenspace at [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline].  The exponential solution built from this eigenvector is  [mathjax]\\quad e^{-t} \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ -1 \\\\\\ 3 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Steps 3. Check whether there are enough independent solutions and write the general solution.**  We have three independent solutions,  [mathjax]e^{2t} \\begin{pmatrix} 1/2 \\\\\\ 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}, \\quad e^{2t} \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}, \\quad e^{-t} \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ -1 \\\\\\ 3 \\end{pmatrix},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so they form a basis of all solutions. The general solution is  [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{\\begin{pmatrix} x \\\\\\ y \\\\\\ z \\end{pmatrix} = c_1 e^{2t} \\begin{pmatrix} 1/2 \\\\\\ 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} + c_2 e^{2t} \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix} + c_3 e^{-t} \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ -1 \\\\\\ 3 \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline].  If there were initial conditions, we could solve for [mathjaxinline]c_1,c_2,c_3[/mathjaxinline] to get a specific solution. Recall that we have found (in the last lecture) the eigenvalues and eigenspace of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] to be  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text{Eigenvalue}[/mathjaxinline] |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Corresponding eigenspace}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.24)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda =0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ;[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Span}\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ -1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.25)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda =1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ;[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Span}\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.26)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda =2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ;[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Span}\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.27)      ###  Solution  The eigenvalues are all distinct, so we automatically have enough independent eigenvectors. The exponential solutions [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}[/mathjaxinline] are  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}, \\quad \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}e^{t} , \\quad \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}e^{2t} ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the general solution is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1 \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix} + c_2 \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}e^{t} + c_3 \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}e^{2t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.28)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      (If there were initial conditions, we could solve for [mathjaxinline]c_1,c_2,c_3[/mathjaxinline] to get a specific solution.) {"pageid": 141, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@05_homog/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@05_homog-tab6", "text": "The following theorems are straight-forward generalizations of the ones for [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] systems.  **Dimension theorem for a homogeneous linear system of ODEs.** For any first- order homogeneous linear system of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] ODEs in [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] unknown functions  [mathjax]\\dot{{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} } = \\mathbf{A}(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      the set of solutions is an [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional vector space.  The dimension theorem is a consequence of the existence and uniqueness theorem:     **Existence and uniqueness theorem for a linear system of ODEs.** Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}(t)[/mathjaxinline] be a square matrix-valued function and let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{r}(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] be a vector-valued function, both continuous on an open time interval [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline]. Let [mathjaxinline]a \\in I[/mathjaxinline], and let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{b}[/mathjaxinline] be a vector. Then there exists a unique solution [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} (t)[/mathjaxinline] to the system  [mathjax]\\dot{{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} } = \\mathbf{A}(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} + \\mathbf{r}(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      satisfying the initial condition  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} (a) = \\mathbf{b}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that for [mathjaxinline]n\\times n\\,[/mathjaxinline] systems, the initial condition really consists of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] conditions, one for each component of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} x_1(a)\\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ x_n(a)\\end{pmatrix}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} b_1\\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ b_n\\end{pmatrix}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]  In other words, to pin down one solution to a first order linear system, we need to specify the initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} (a) = \\mathbf{b},\\,[/mathjaxinline] which consists of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] equations, one for each component, for [mathjaxinline]\\, n\\times n\\,[/mathjaxinline] systems.    ###  How does the existence and uniqueness theorem lead to the dimension theorem?  First, set [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{r}(t)=\\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] for a homogenous system. Secondly, by the existence and uniqueness theorem, once the starting time [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] is fixed, the solutions to the system are in 1-to-1 correspondence to the possibilities for the initial condition vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{b}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Therefore, the set of solutions to the homogeneous system is [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  In most cases, we will consider the differential equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{r}(t).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.37)   ---|---|---|---      In other words, we assume [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is **constant, independent of** [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], i.e. [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}(t)=\\mathbf{A}.\\,[/mathjaxinline] We will also assume in most cases that [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is **complete** , i.e. the dimension of the eigenspace for each eigenvalue is equal to the multiplicity of the eigenvalue. When [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{r}(t)=\\mathbf{0},\\,[/mathjaxinline] the general solution to the homogeneous equation, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline], takes the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(t) = c_1 \\mathbf v_1 e^{\\lambda _1 t} + \\cdots c_n \\mathbf v_n e^{\\lambda _n t},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.38)   ---|---|---|---      where the eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _i[/mathjaxinline] may not be distinct, but the exponential solutions [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_i e^{\\lambda _i t}[/mathjaxinline] are linearly independent. This is consistent with the dimension theorem because this is an [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional family of solutions.  Theory of 2 by 2 systems", "filename": "05_homog-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Theory of 2 by 2 systems"}

To repeat the example above, choose [mathjaxinline]k_1=k_2=k_3=k[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]m_1=m_2=m.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Recall that [mathjaxinline]\\omega ^2= \\frac{k}{m}[/mathjaxinline].  To adjust initial positions [mathjaxinline]x_1,\\, x_2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] drag the masses on the diagram; to adjust initial velocities, check the boxes next to [mathjaxinline]\\, v_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]v_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] and drag the end of the vertical bar on the left of the mass. The graph on the right displays the evolution of any of [mathjaxinline]\\, x_1(t),\\, x_2(t),\\, v_1(t),\\, v_2(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] that you have checked on the left.    Choose initial conditions that result in the pure sinusoidal modes and watch the action.  Then explore solutions resulting from other initial conditions. These solutions are linear combinations of the two pure sinusoidal modes. Because the pure sinusoids are at different frequencies, their linear combinations look chaotic. In fact, because [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt3[/mathjaxinline] is an irrational number, there are no periodic solutions except for the two pure sinusoidal modes.    To stay within the simplifying assumptions of our model, choose initial [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x_2[/mathjaxinline] to be between [mathjaxinline]-0.5[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]0.5[/mathjaxinline], and keep [mathjaxinline]v_1=v_2=0[/mathjaxinline]. The two masses will not collide and the spring will not be too compressed. If you are outside this range, our model does not work, and you may see non-physical phenomena where the masses cross each other without interacting.    In the graph on the right, you will see that graphs of [mathjaxinline]x_1(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x_2(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] intersect. Note that each of these functions are displayed relative to the equilibrium positions of the corresponding mass, and that intersections of these graphs correspond the two masses being at the same displacements away from their respective equilibrium positions, rather than the two masses colliding physically.    Explore the system with different masses and spring constants by adjusting the respective sliders!  mathlet", "filename": "05_homog-tab16-text1.html", "title": "mathlet"}

{"pageid": 146, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@03_fundspaces/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@03_fundspaces-tab3", "text": "**Steps to compute a basis for** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A})}}[/mathjaxinline] **:**    1. Perform Gaussian elimination to convert [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] to a matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] in row echelon form.     2. Identify the pivot columns of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline].     3. The corresponding columns of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] are a basis for [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline].   ###  Proof that the algorithm finds a basis for column space. (*)  Recall that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] is a row echelon form of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]. Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf C[/mathjaxinline] be the _reduced_ row echelon form of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]. If  [mathjax]\\text{fifth column} = 3 (\\text{first column}) + 7 (\\text{second column})[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is true for a matrix, it will remain true after any row operation.  Similarly, any linear relation between columns is preserved by row operations. So the linear relations between columns of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] are the same as the linear relations between columns of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf C[/mathjaxinline]. The condition that certain numbered columns (say the first, second, and fourth) of a matrix form a basis is expressible in terms of which linear relations hold. So if certain columns form a basis for [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf C)[/mathjaxinline], the same numbered columns will form a basis for [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline]. **Warning:** these are very unlikely to be the same columns!  Recall that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] is a row echelon form of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]. We can obtain the reduced row echelon form [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf C[/mathjaxinline] by performing Gauss- Jordan elimination on [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline]. This process does not change the pivot locations. Thus it will be enough to show that the pivot columns of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf C[/mathjaxinline] form a basis of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf C)[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf C[/mathjaxinline] is in reduced row echelon form, the pivot columns of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf C[/mathjaxinline] are the first [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] of the [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] standard basis vectors for [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^m[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] is the number of nonzero rows of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf C[/mathjaxinline]. These columns are linearly **independent,** and every other column is a linear combination of them, since the entries of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf C[/mathjaxinline] below the first [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] rows are all zeros. Thus the pivot columns of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf C[/mathjaxinline] form a basis of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf C)[/mathjaxinline].  (The symbol (*) after the title means that you are not required to know this proof for any exam in this class.)  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  In particular,  [mathjax]\\boxed { \\dim \\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A}) = \\\\# \\text{ pivot columns of } \\mathbf{B}. }[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Warning:** Usually [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A}) \\ne \\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{B})[/mathjaxinline].  Algorithm", "filename": "03_fundspaces-tab3-text2.html", "title": "Algorithm"}

{"pageid": 148, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@05_homog/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@05_homog-tab2", "text": "Below we will go through another example which yields exactly the same system of differential equations as in the video.    You've been put in charge of part of a medicine manufacturing plant with three identical cylindrical storage tanks. These tanks are filled with the medicine to different heights and are connected to each other via a pipe at their bottoms, with valves that are initially closed. Our goal is to determine how the fluid will flow once we open the valves. Note that we have solved the analogous problem for two tanks in the course _Differential equations: 2 by 2 systems_ previously.    To begin, we name the heights of the fluid in the three tanks [mathjaxinline]h_1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]h_2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, h_3\\,[/mathjaxinline] respectively.  ![](/static/images/tanks.svg)   Three tanks cyclically connected to each other  **Simplifying assumptions**  We will make the simplifying assumptions that we can model the flow linearly, and that the flow rate is proportional to the difference in fluid height (as in the case with only 2 tanks). These assumptions are valid when the pipes have a small diameter relative to the overall size of the tanks, the geometry of the pipes and tanks is simple, and the fluid properties of the medicine work out.  **Equation for tank 1:**   Let us first work out the differential equation describing fluid flow into tank 1. Let [mathjaxinline]V_1[/mathjaxinline] be the volume of fluid in tank 1. The flow rate of fluid into (or out of) tank [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] is by definition [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\frac{dV_1}{dt}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]    As mentioned above, we assume that the flow rate is proportional to the difference in heights. The flow rate into tank 1 from tank 2 is [mathjaxinline]b (h_2-h_1),\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] is the constant of proportionality (with dimension [mathjaxinline][\\text{length}]^2 [\\text{time}]^{-1}).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Similarly, the flow rate from tank 3 is [mathjaxinline]c (h_3-h_1),\\,[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] the constant of proportionality. The flow rate into tank 1 is therefore:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dV_1}{dt}\\,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b (h_2-h_1) +c (h_3-h_1).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.1)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Note that the constant [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] is positive because when [mathjaxinline]h_2>h_1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] fluid flows into tank 1 so that [mathjaxinline]V_1[/mathjaxinline] is increasing. Similarly, [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is positive. We usually set up differential equations so that parameters such as [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] are positive. This way we will be less prone to sign errors.    Since the tank is cylindrical, the rate of change in volume [mathjaxinline]\\, V_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] is given by the cross sectional area [mathjaxinline]\\, A\\,[/mathjaxinline] times the rate of change in height [mathjaxinline]h_1[/mathjaxinline] of fluid in tank 1 :  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dV_1}{dt} = A \\frac{dh_1}{dt}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.2)   ---|---|---|---      Therefore, the differential equation in terms of [mathjaxinline]h_1[/mathjaxinline] is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dh_1}{dt}\\, = \\frac{1}{A} \\frac{dV_1}{dt} \\, =\\, \\frac{b}{A} (h_2-h_1) +\\frac{c}{A} (h_3-h_1).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.3)   ---|---|---|---      We can combine the constants. Let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle a_{21} = \\frac{b}{A}[/mathjaxinline] (with dimension [mathjaxinline][\\text{time}]^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]), where the subscript [mathjaxinline]21[/mathjaxinline] indicates that this is the constant governing the flow from tank 2 to tank 1. Similarly, let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle a_{31}=\\frac{c}{A}[/mathjaxinline] be the combined constant governing flow from tank 3 and tank 1. The differential equation in terms of the new constants is:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dh_1}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a_{21} (h_2-h_1)+a_{31} (h_3-h_1)\\qquad (a_{21},\\, a_{31}>0).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.4)   ---|---|---|---|---|---       **Equations for tank 2 and tank 3:**    Analogous reasoning as above gives the differential equations for flow rates into tank 2 and tank 3:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dh_2}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a_{12} (h_1-h_2)+a_{32} (h_3-h_2) \\qquad (a_{12},\\, a_{32}>0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.5)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dh_3}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a_{13} (h_1-h_3)+a_{23} (h_2-h_3) \\qquad (a_{13},\\, a_{23}>0).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.6)      Note that [mathjaxinline]\\, a_{12}=a_{21}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] For example, if [mathjaxinline]h_2>h_1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]\\, a_{21} (h_2-h_1)>0[/mathjaxinline] so the flow rate from tank 2 into tank 1 is positive, whereas [mathjaxinline]a_{12} (h_1-h_2)<0[/mathjaxinline] so that the flow rate from tank 1 to tank 2 is negative. This is consistent because these 2 expressions are equal in magnitude but opposite in sign. Similarly, [mathjaxinline]\\, a_{13}=a_{31},\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, a_{23}=a_{32}.[/mathjaxinline]  **Matrix form**   We can now rewrite this equation in matrix form:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\qquad \\, \\text{where }\\, \\mathbf{x}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2\\\\\\ h_3 \\end{pmatrix},\\, \\, \\, \\mathbf{A}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} -a_{12}-a_{13} & a_{12} & a_{13} \\\\\\ a_{12} & -a_{12}-a_{23} & a_{23} \\\\\\ a_{13} & a_{23} & -a_{13}-a_{23} \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.7)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      To make things even nicer, we'll set all constants [mathjaxinline]a_{ij}=1[/mathjaxinline]. The resulting equation is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\qquad \\, \\text{where }\\, \\mathbf{x}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2\\\\\\ h_3 \\end{pmatrix},\\, \\, \\, \\mathbf{A}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} -2 & 1 & 1 \\\\\\ 1 & -2 & 1 \\\\\\ 1 & 1 & -2 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.8)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      ###  Symmetry  Note that the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is symmetric, i.e. [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}=\\mathbf{A}^{T}\\,[/mathjaxinline] (even before the constants are set to [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]). Is this a coincidence? In fact, symmetric matrices appear in many models of real physical phenomena.  An important theorem in linear algebra states that symmetric matrices have real eigenvalues and an orthogonal basis of eigenvectors. We will see how these properties are useful in the next lecture. {"pageid": 150, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@partB02/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@partB02-tab2", "text": "### Diffusion   **Diffusion** is the intermingling of one substance into another substance based on the movement of the particles. For example, when you put a sugar cube into a cup of coffee, the first thing that happens is that the sugar dissolves. Once it dissolves, the sugar particles begin to spread through the coffee. This is known as diffusion. Eventually, even the top layer is sweet (even though there may be an undissolved layer of sugary coffee at the bottom).  The diffusion process is ubiquitous throughout science: we may be interested in how heat diffuses in the handle of a frying pan, or how the hormones in birth control pills diffuse in the human body. To understand how diffusion works, we need a mathematical model.  ### Simplifying assumptions  As a first step, we will consider a one dimensional model in which one substance (say sugar) diffuses along an interval of the real line (perhaps a very thin test tube of coffee).  ![Thin horizontal tube.](/static/images/diffusion_1.svg)      We will model the sugar as discrete particles or molecules.  ![Thin horizontal tube with particles inside.](/static/images/diffusion_2.svg)      In addition, we will break up the interval into distinct subintervals, and look at how many particles move from one subinterval into the adjacent subintervals.  ![Thin horizontal tube with particles inside. The tube is divided into subintervals which are indicated by vertical lines.](/static/images/diffusion_3.svg)      Once we make this restriction, we can model the real line as a series of nodes. At each moment in time, the number of particles at each node is determined by the number of particles on the corresponding subinterval.  ![Horizontal line with equally spaced nodes.](/static/images/diffusion_4.svg)      ### Random walks  The way we model the diffusion of sugar along this series of nodes is to consider the sugar particles as random walkers. A **random walk** is a path taken by the random walker, starting at one node, and moving to one or the other nodes at each step. The sense in which the path is random is that we consider more than one possible path, and assign a probability to each path.  For example, for each time step [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline], the random walker has an equal probability of moving one node to the right, or one node to the left. No walker stays stationary. Note that a random walker can only move into adjacent nodes, they cannot teleport! Also, if a random walker is all the way at the endpoint on the left, they can only move to the right, and vice versa.  The following animation shows a histogram of the distribution of particles at each node along a graph. The positions of these particles are shown over several consecutive time steps.  Random walkers", "filename": "partB02-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Random walkers"}
