{"pageid": 152, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@04_eigenthings/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@04_eigenthings-tab5", "text": "Since eigenvalues are roots of a polynomial with real coefficients, they can be complex, and when they are, they come in pairs of complex conjugates.     **Example 5.1** Find the eigenvalues of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1 & 0 \\\\\\ 1 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline]   (This matrix represents the function that rotates any vector in [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]\\, 90^\\circ \\,[/mathjaxinline] counterclockwise about the [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline]-axis.)     **Solution** :  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I})[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{vmatrix} -\\lambda & -1 & 0 \\\\\\ 1 & -\\lambda & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 1-\\lambda \\end{vmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\lambda ^2+1)(1-\\lambda )[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -(\\lambda +i)(\\lambda -i)(\\lambda -1)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\pm i,\\, 1.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Hence, the eigenvalues are [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =\\pm i,1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] (each with multiplicity [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]). Note that both [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] and its conjugate [mathjaxinline]-i[/mathjaxinline] are eigenvalues.  **Theorem 5.2** For any [mathjaxinline]n \\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix, the total number of complex eigenvalues, counted with multiplicity, is [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline].  Note that complex eigenvalues include real eigenvalues.  ###  Proof  We apply the fundamental theorem of algebra to the characteristic polynomial of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], which is a degree [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] polynomial with real coefficients.  **The fundamental theorem of algebra:** Every nonzero degree [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] polynomial with complex coefficients has exactly [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] complex roots when counted with multiplicity.  Remember real numbers are also complex numbers, so this implies in particular that every nonzero degree [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] polynomial with real coefficients, e.g. the characteristic polynomial of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A},[/mathjaxinline] has exactly [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] complex roots when counted with multiplicity. {"pageid": 155, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@05_homog/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@05_homog-tab15", "text": "Let us continue with finding the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the companion matrix of the unforced coupled oscillator:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\, \\mathbf{A}=\\begin{pmatrix} 0 & \\mathbf{I}\\\\\\ \\mathbf{B}& 0 \\end{pmatrix} \\qquad \\text{where } \\, \\mathbf{B}=\\omega ^2 \\begin{pmatrix} -2 & 1 \\\\\\ 1 & -2 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.87)   ---|---|---|---       **Eigenvalues**  Let us compute the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{B}\\,[/mathjaxinline]. The characteristic polynomial of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]\\mathrm{det}(\\lambda \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{B})\\, =\\, \\lambda ^2+4\\omega ^2\\lambda +3\\omega ^4\\, =\\, (\\lambda +\\omega ^2)(\\lambda +3\\omega ^2),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{B}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are [mathjaxinline]-\\omega ^2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-3\\omega ^2[/mathjaxinline].  We know that the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] are the square roots of the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore, the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] are  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\pm i\\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\pm \\sqrt3i\\omega .[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.88)   ---|---|---|---|---|---       **Eigenvectors**  Let us find the eigenvectors for [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline]. (We are almost there!)  For the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]-\\omega ^2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] we need to find a basis for the null space of  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{B}-(-\\omega ^2 \\mathbf{I})=\\omega ^2\\begin{pmatrix} -1& 1\\\\\\ 1& -1\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.89)   ---|---|---|---      The vector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] will do.  Similarly, an eigenvector for the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]-3\\omega ^2\\,[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].  Recall from the previous page that the eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] with eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda \\,[/mathjaxinline] are [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} \\mathbf{x}\\\\\\ \\lambda \\mathbf{x}\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is an eigenvector of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{B}\\,[/mathjaxinline] with eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda ^2[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore, the four pairs of eigenvalues and eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] are  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text{for } \\lambda \\, = \\, \\pm i\\omega \\, :\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ \\pm i\\omega \\\\\\ \\pm i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}\\quad ,\\quad \\text{for } \\lambda \\, \\, = \\, \\, \\pm i\\sqrt3\\omega \\, :\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -1\\\\\\ \\pm i\\sqrt3\\omega \\\\\\ \\mp i\\sqrt3\\omega \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.90)   ---|---|---|---      Note that as in the [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] case, the complex eigenvalues come in pairs of complex conjugates, and the eigenvectors of the conjugate eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\overline{ \\lambda }\\,[/mathjaxinline] are the conjugates of the eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda .[/mathjaxinline]     **Solutions to the companion system**  The four pairs of eigenvalues and eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] give the four exponential solutions:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle e^{i\\omega t}\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}\\quad ,\\quad e^{i\\sqrt3\\omega t}\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -1\\\\\\ i\\sqrt3\\omega \\\\\\ -i\\sqrt3\\omega \\end{pmatrix},\\qquad \\text{and their complex conjugates}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.91)   ---|---|---|---      The general (complex) solution is therefore linear combinations of these.     **The real solutions and physical interpretation**  But we are interested in the real solutions because the components of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}=\\begin{pmatrix} x_1\\\\\\ x_2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] represent the displacements in real physical space of the two masses.    As usual, we find a basis for the real solutions by taking the real and imaginary parts of the exponential solutions.  Since the bottom half [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{y}\\,[/mathjaxinline] of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} \\mathbf{x}\\\\\\ \\mathbf{y}\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{y}=\\dot{\\mathbf{x}},\\,[/mathjaxinline] we only need to write down the top halves of the real solutions:  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} \\cos (\\omega t)\\\\\\ \\cos (\\omega t)\\end{pmatrix}\\quad ,\\quad \\begin{pmatrix} \\sin (\\omega t)\\\\\\ \\sin (\\omega t)\\end{pmatrix}\\quad ,\\quad \\begin{pmatrix} \\cos (\\sqrt3\\omega t)\\\\\\ -\\cos (\\sqrt3\\omega t)\\end{pmatrix}\\quad ,\\quad \\begin{pmatrix} \\sin (\\sqrt3\\omega t)\\\\\\ -\\sin (\\sqrt3\\omega t)\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The first two solutions combine to give a general sinusoid of angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] **and** [mathjaxinline]x_2=x_1[/mathjaxinline]. In this mode, the masses are moving together; the spring between them is relaxed.  The general solution is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A_1\\cos (\\omega t+\\phi _1)+A_2\\cos (\\sqrt3 \\omega t+\\phi _2)[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.92)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A_1\\cos (\\omega t+\\phi _1)-A_2\\cos (\\sqrt3 \\omega t+\\phi _2).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.93)      There are two purely sinusoidal modes:    * When [mathjaxinline]A_2=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]x_1=x_2=A_1\\cos (\\omega t+\\phi _1),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the two masses oscillate together with the spring in between at equilibrium,     * When [mathjaxinline]A_1=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]x_1=-x_2= A_2\\cos (\\sqrt3 \\omega t+\\phi _2),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the oscillations are synchronous but in opposite directions.   **Demonstration of coupled oscillator using air carts**  The Technical Services Group in the physics department has graciously provided some video footage of the couple oscillator in real action using carts on an air track.    The springs are difficult to discern in the video, and at the outset the carts have brakes on. When the technician turns on the switch, the carts become elevated on an air track and move. This air track makes the assumption of zero drag quite close to reality.  **Video note:** In the video below, the segment relevant to this example ends at 1:07, but we include the rest of the demonstration for fun. "text": "In general, given [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] functions [mathjaxinline]f_1(\\mathbf{x}), f_2(\\mathbf{x}) \\dotsc ,f_n(\\mathbf{x})[/mathjaxinline], defined for vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline], the best linear approximation to this vector valued function near the point ([mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]-vector) [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{a}[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} f_1(\\mathbf{x}) \\\\\\ f_2(\\mathbf{x}) \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ f_n(\\mathbf{x}) \\end{pmatrix} \\approx \\underset {{\\color{blue}{\\text{value at } \\mathbf{a}}} }{\\begin{pmatrix} f_1(\\mathbf{a}) \\\\\\ f_2(\\mathbf{a}) \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ f_n(\\mathbf{a}) \\end{pmatrix}} + \\underset {{\\color{blue}{\\text{derivative at } \\mathbf{a} }} }{ \\left. \\begin{pmatrix} \\partial {f_1}/\\partial {x_1} & \\partial {f_1}/\\partial {x_2} & \\dotsb & \\partial {f_1}/\\partial {x_n} \\\\\\ \\partial {f_2}/\\partial {x_1} & \\partial {f_2}/\\partial {x_2} & \\dotsb & \\partial {f_2}/\\partial {x_n} \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\vdots & \\vdots \\\\\\ \\partial {f_n}/\\partial {x_1} & \\partial {f_n}/\\partial {x_2} & \\dotsb & \\partial {f_n}/\\partial {x_n} \\end{pmatrix} \\right|_{\\mathbf{a}}} \\begin{pmatrix} \\mathbf{x}- \\mathbf{a} \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{J}= \\begin{pmatrix} \\partial {f_1}/\\partial {x_1} & \\partial {f_1}/\\partial {x_2} & \\dotsb & \\partial {f_1}/\\partial {x_n} \\\\\\ \\partial {f_2}/\\partial {x_1} & \\partial {f_2}/\\partial {x_2} & \\dotsb & \\partial {f_2}/\\partial {x_n} \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\vdots & \\vdots \\\\\\ \\partial {f_n}/\\partial {x_1} & \\partial {f_n}/\\partial {x_2} & \\dotsb & \\partial {f_n}/\\partial {x_n} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] is called the **Jacobian matrix** .  We can rewrite this linearization using more compact notation as  [mathjax]\\mathbf{f}\\approx \\mathbf{f}(\\mathbf{a}) + \\mathbf{J}(\\mathbf{a})(\\mathbf{x}-\\mathbf{a}), \\qquad \\mathbf{f}= \\begin{pmatrix} f_1 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ f_n \\end{pmatrix}, \\mathbf{x}= \\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ x_n \\end{pmatrix}, \\, \\mathbf{a} = \\begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ a_n \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that this is exactly the same notation we had in the [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] case.  To determine the stability of the system at the critical points, you evaluate the Jacobian at each critical point. If all of the eigenvalues of the Jacobian at a point [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{a}[/mathjaxinline] have negative real part, the critical point is stable. If there is an eigenvalue with positive real part, the critical point is unstable. (However, if the highest real part among eigenvalues is exactly 0, one cannot determine the stability just from the linear approximation of the system.) {"pageid": 161, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@ourcourse/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@ourcourse-tab2", "text": "Differential equations are the mathematical language we use to describe the world around us. Most phenomena can be modeled not by single differential equations, but by systems of interacting differential equations. These systems may consist of many equations. In this course, we will learn how to use linear algebra to solve systems of more than 2 differential equations. We will also learn to use MATLAB to assist us.  We will use systems of equations and matrices to explore    * the original page ranking systems used by Google,     * balancing chemical reaction equations,     * tuned mass dampers and other coupled oscillators,     * 3 or more species competing for resources in an ecosystem,     * the trajectory of a rider on a zipline.   Course Description", "filename": "ourcourse-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Course Description"}

{"pageid": 162, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@6_decoupling/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@6_decoupling-tab9", "text": "![](/static/images/u5s2_heatedbar-v2.svg)  Recall the inhomogeneous system modelling the insulated metal rod with the temperatures at its two ends fixed at [mathjaxinline]x_L[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x_R[/mathjaxinline], and with two thermometers placed at equal distance along it:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt} \\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\\\\\ x_2 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad \\begin{pmatrix} -2 & 1 \\\\\\ 1 & -2 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\\\\\ x_2\\end{pmatrix} + \\begin{pmatrix} x_L \\\\\\ x_R\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] | |   ---|---|---|---|---      **Homogeneous solution**    Let us first consider the case where the end points are held fixed at [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] degree Celsius, so [mathjaxinline]\\, x_L=x_R=0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This makes the system **homogeneous**.    The eigenvalues of the system are [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _1 = -1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _2=-3[/mathjaxinline]. The corresponding eigenvectors are [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].    Hence, a fundamental matrix of the homogeneous system is given by the product:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{X}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1& 1\\\\\\ 1& -1 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} e^{-t} & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & e^{-3t}\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---  Reduce to the homogenous case", "filename": "6_decoupling-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Reduce to the homogenous case"}

It turns out the eigenvectors of a complex eigenvalue are the complex conjugates of the eigenvectors of the conjugate eigenvalue.     **Example 11.1** Find the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1 & 0 \\\\\\ 1 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].      We have found previously that the eigenvalues are [mathjaxinline]1,\\pm i[/mathjaxinline]. Let us now find the eigenvectors. We will start with those of the complex eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline].      **Eigenspace of** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{i}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **:** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{ \\mathrm{NS}(i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}).}}[/mathjaxinline]   We reduce [mathjaxinline]\\, i\\mathbf{I}- \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] to row- echelon form;  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} i & 1 & 0\\\\\\ -1 & i& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& i-1 \\end{pmatrix}\\rightarrow \\begin{pmatrix} i & 1 & 0\\\\\\ 0 & 0& -1\\\\\\ 0& 0& 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.14)   ---|---|---|---      By back substitution (the first equation is [mathjaxinline]ix+y=0\\,[/mathjaxinline] ), the solutions are [mathjaxinline]c \\begin{pmatrix} i \\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] for any scalar [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline]. That is,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text{Eigenspace of }\\, i\\, =\\, \\mathrm{NS}\\left(i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}\\right)\\, =\\, \\mathrm{Span}\\begin{pmatrix} i\\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.15)   ---|---|---|---       **Eigenspace of** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{-i}}[/mathjaxinline] **:** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{ \\mathrm{NS}(-i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}).}}[/mathjaxinline]   Since [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a real matrix, [mathjaxinline]\\, -i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is the complex conjugate of [mathjaxinline]\\, i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A},\\,[/mathjaxinline] and every step in the Gaussian elimination is the same as before except with [mathjaxinline]\\, i\\,[/mathjaxinline] replaced by [mathjaxinline]\\, -i\\,[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle - i \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} -i & 1 & 0\\\\\\ -1 & -i& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& -i-1 \\end{pmatrix}\\rightarrow \\begin{pmatrix} i & -1 & 0\\\\\\ 0 & 0& -1\\\\\\ 0& 0& 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.16)   ---|---|---|---      Therefore, the row-echelon form of [mathjaxinline]\\, -i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is the complex conjugate of the row echelon form of [mathjaxinline]\\, i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the vectors in the nullspace of [mathjaxinline]\\, -i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] are the complex conjugates of the vectors in the nullspace of [mathjaxinline]\\, i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline]. Hence,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text{Eigenspace of }\\, -i\\, =\\, \\mathrm{NS}\\left(-i\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}\\right)\\, =\\, \\mathrm{Span}\\begin{pmatrix} -i\\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.17)   ---|---|---|---       **Eigenspace of** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{1}}[/mathjaxinline] **:** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{ \\mathrm{NS}(\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}).}}[/mathjaxinline]   We start by reducing [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1& 1 & 0\\\\\\ -1 & 1& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& 0 \\end{pmatrix}\\rightarrow \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0\\\\\\ 0 & 1& 0\\\\\\ 0& 0& 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.18)   ---|---|---|---      This gives the eigenspace  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text{Eigenspace of }\\, 1\\, =\\, \\mathrm{NS}\\left(\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Span}\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.19)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      (You could also have guessed the solution [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v= \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] and plugged it into [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] to check that indeed it is an eigenvector of eigenvalue 1.)  **Conclusion** : The eigenvalues and corresponding eigenspaces of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1 & 0 \\\\\\ 1 & 0 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] are:  | i\\\\\\ 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.21)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda =-i[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ;[/mathjaxinline] | {"pageid": 164, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@03_fundspaces/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@03_fundspaces-tab3", "text": "**Definition 3.1** The **column space** of a matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is the span of its columns. The notation for it is [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A})}}[/mathjaxinline]. (It is also called the **image** of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], and written [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{Im\\, }(\\mathbf{A})}}[/mathjaxinline].)  Since [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline] is a span, it is a vector space.  **Example 3.2** Consider the matrix [mathjaxinline]A = \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 2 & 3 \\\\\\ 2 & 4 & 6 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline]. Its column space is given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A}) = \\text{the span of } \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 2 \\end{pmatrix}, \\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\\\ 4 \\end{pmatrix}, \\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\\\\\ 6 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Using that the column vectors are all constant multiples of the vector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], we find a basis for the column space consisting of the single vector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], and find that [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline] is the line [mathjaxinline]y=2x[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 3.3** Find a basis for the column space of the matrix  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 2 & 3 \\\\\\ -1 & -2 & -3 \\\\\\ 1 & 2 & 3 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 9 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      The column space is defined as [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Span}\\left(\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ -1 \\\\\\ 1 \\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}, \\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\\\ -2 \\\\\\ 2 \\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}, \\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\\\\\ -3 \\\\\\ 3 \\\\\\ 9\\end{pmatrix} \\right)[/mathjaxinline]. But the second vector is a multiple of the first vector, so it is redundant. Therefore, the column space can be described more simply as the span of the first and third columns:  [mathjax]\\mathrm{CS}(\\mathbf{A}) = \\mathrm{Span}\\left(\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ -1 \\\\\\ 1 \\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}, \\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\\\\\ -3 \\\\\\ 3 \\\\\\ 9\\end{pmatrix} \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      These two vectors are linearly independent, so we do need both vectors in the basis for this column space.  Column Space", "filename": "03_fundspaces-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Column Space"}

{"pageid": 165, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingalinearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingalinearsystems-tab2", "text": "### Using reduced row echelon form  Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{R}[/mathjaxinline] be the reduced row echelon form [mathjaxinline]\\texttt{rref}(\\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline]. Then the solutions to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] are the same as the solutions to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{R} \\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline], which is the system  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{orange}{a}} \\phantom{+b+c} - 2{\\color{blue}{d}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\phantom{a+} {\\color{orange}{b}} \\phantom{+c} - {\\color{blue}{d}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\phantom{a+b+ }{\\color{orange}{c}} - {\\color{blue}{d}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The **pivot variables** are **[mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]** , **[mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline]** , and **[mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline]** . The only **free variable** is **[mathjaxinline]d[/mathjaxinline]** . We set the free variable **[mathjaxinline]d[/mathjaxinline]** equal to a parameter, say [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. For each pivot variable, there is an equation expressing it in terms of **[mathjaxinline]d[/mathjaxinline]** , so we can immediately write down the general solution in terms of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{d}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{orange}{a}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2t[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{orange}{b}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{orange}{c}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t.[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Finishing the example", "filename": "02_solvingalinearsystems-tab2-text2.html", "title": "Finishing the example"}

{"pageid": 166, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@8_nonlinear/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@8_nonlinear-tab5", "text": "Now we want to add a dynamic rider into our model. There are two limiting cases we can consider first.    1. A heavy rider and a light (massless) cable. In this case the path of the rider is an ellipse because at all points along the rider trajectory, the cable will be pulled into straight lines.     2. A very light (massless) rider and a very heavy cable. In this case the path of the rider is the catenary because the rider is not heavy enough to deform the shape of the hanging cable.   Of course, in designing a zipline to be used with human riders, we are not in either of these two limiting cases. In general a human rider will weigh between 25 and 100 kilograms. And a zipline cable of between 200-600 meters long will weigh between 20 and 400 kilograms, depending on the type of cable used. So the trajectories that we will see will be much more interesting.  What we do know is that the trajectory of a rider should lie somewhere inside the ellipse, and should typically be below the catenary connecting the two end points of the zipline (assuming no crazy bouncing). The mathlet visualization below shows you these two limiting case, and allows you to change the positions of the end point of the right hand side of the zipline, change the mass of the rider, and the horizontal position of the rider to see the static position of the rider in each case that a force is applied to the rider to prevent further movement. {"pageid": 168, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@04_eigenthings/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@04_eigenthings-tab17", "text": "While we've studied a lot of physical systems in this class, there are many non-physical systems that use linear algebra. One rich source of applications is computational science. We'll give one example here, an early version of the **pagerank algorithm** used by Google and other search engines to determine the order of results in a query. To define this rigorously, we'll use the tools of linear algebra. What we will do here will not be the exact pagerank algorithm, but will get across the general idea while also providing some linear algebra practice.  ###  Some Pagerank History  Prior to the invention of pagerank, most search engines found and ranked results by counting the number of times a keyword appears on a page. This could be and was easily abused, and would often return pages that had hidden a particular keyword in the background in 2pt font. This algorithm had no way of taking into account the general popularity of a web page, and the winners of a search were always just those who said the keyword most.  A new idea, which was worked out by Google founders Larry Page and Sergey Brin, was to use the number of links to a webpage to determine how to rank it. An important and popular webpage will have a large number of links pointing to it. Likewise, links from other important webpages will be worth more than links from random pages with no value.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Working through the problems below will both provide excellent linear algebra practice as well as teach you about the pagerank algorithm.  **Definitions and Problems**  In order to show how pagerank works, we'll work through a series of examples. First imagine we have three webpages: Wikipedia, Facebook, and Buzzfeed. Let's assume this is the entire internet, and the percentage of people on each page at a time is [mathjaxinline]W[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline] respectively. Now we need to find the number of links between each page. We'll store this information in a matrix, calling this matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{P}[/mathjaxinline]. Starting with no links, we write  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{P}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 & 0\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Now to start filling in this matrix. Suppose Buzzfeed has six links to Facebook, and four links to Wikipedia. In our matrix, the column represents where the link is coming **from** , and the row represents where the link is going **to** . So for the links from Buzzfeed to Facebook, the matrix becomes  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{P}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 & 0\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 6\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      and then adding the links to Wikipedia, we get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{P}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 & 4\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 6\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      The matrix we are constructing is called the adjacency matrix. Each entry represents a connection from one node to another in a graph. This is a useful way of storing information dealing with different objects and directed connections between them.  **Problem 17.1** Fill in the remainder of the adjacency matrix. Suppose that Wikipedia has one link to each Facebook and Buzzfeed, and Facebook has one link to Buzzfeed and two links to Wikipedia. What is our resultant matrix?  ###  Solution  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{P}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 2 & 4\\\\\\ 1 & 0 & 6\\\\\\ 1 & 1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Now that we have an adjacency matrix constructed, we can move forward and begin to attempt a ranking. To do this, we have to find the eigenvalues.  **Problem 17.2** Find the eigenvalues of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{P}[/mathjaxinline]. Which eigenvalue has the largest absolute value?  ###  Solution  The eigenvalues are the solutions of the equation  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 = \\mathrm{det}\\left(\\mathbf{P}- \\lambda \\mathbf{I}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   Plugging in numbers we get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0=\\mathrm{det}\\begin{pmatrix} -\\lambda & 2 & 4\\\\\\ 1 & -\\lambda & 6\\\\\\ 1 & 1 & -\\lambda \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   Computing the determinant gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 = -\\lambda ^3 + 4 + 12 + 6 \\lambda + 2\\lambda + 4 \\lambda .[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   Simplifying we see that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 = \\lambda ^3 - 12\\lambda - 16.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   We search for a root and find one, [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1 = -2[/mathjaxinline], and then factoring gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0=(\\lambda +2)(\\lambda ^2 - 2\\lambda -8).[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   Now factoring the last term we get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 = (\\lambda +2)(\\lambda +2)(\\lambda -4),[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   so our last two eigenvalues are  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -2,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda _3[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 4.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   Now we have found three eigenvalues, and the eigenvalue with the largest absolute value is [mathjaxinline]4[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Why do we care about the eigenvalue that has the largest absolute value? Qualitatively, if we watch the path of a user as they browse the web, this is like applying the matrix to an initial state vector repeatedly. The eigenvector with the largest eigenvalue will dominate. So this eigenvector will give us the best ranking.  **Problem 17.3** Find the eigenvector corresponding to the eigenvalue of largest absolute value.  ###  Solution  Finding the eigenvector is equivalent to finding the null space of the matrix |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 4\\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{P}=\\begin{pmatrix} 4 & -2 & -4\\\\\\ -1 & 4 & -6\\\\\\ -1 & -1 & 4 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   To find the null space we use Gauss\u2013Jordan elimination. We divide the first row by [mathjaxinline]4[/mathjaxinline] and then add it to the second and third rows getting  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -\\frac{1}{2} & -1\\\\\\ 0 & \\frac{7}{2} & -7\\\\\\ 0 & \\frac{3}{2} & -3 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   Now we divide the second row by [mathjaxinline]7/2[/mathjaxinline] to get  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -\\frac{1}{2} & -1\\\\\\ 0 & 1 & -2\\\\\\ 0 & \\frac{3}{2} & -3 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   We now subtract [mathjaxinline]\\frac{3}{2}\\left(\\text{row }2\\right)[/mathjaxinline] from the [mathjaxinline]\\text{row }3[/mathjaxinline], and add [mathjaxinline]\\frac{1}{2}\\left(\\text{row }2\\right)[/mathjaxinline] to the [mathjaxinline]\\text{row } 1[/mathjaxinline], to get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & -2\\\\\\ 0 & 1 & -2\\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   Now from inspection we see that a vector in the nullspace is  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{v} = \\begin{pmatrix} 2\\\\\\ 2\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   Any vector in the nullspace is an eigenvector, so [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] is an eigenvector of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{P}[/mathjaxinline]. Now we can use this vector as a rough ranking of our websites; Wikipedia and Facebook each have a rank of [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline], and Buzzfeed has a rank of [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Application: the Pagerank Algorithm", "filename": "04_eigenthings-tab17-text1.html", "title": "Application: the Pagerank Algorithm"}

{"pageid": 169, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@05_homog/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@05_homog-tab10", "text": "Recall from the course _Differential equations: 2 by 2 systems_ that any second order linear ODE can be converted to a first order linear system called its **companion system**.  **Problem 10.1** Convert [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x} + 5 \\dot{x} + 6 x = 0[/mathjaxinline] to a first-order system of ODEs.  ###  Solution  Define [mathjaxinline]y \\, := \\, \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline]. Then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{x} \\, = \\, - 5 \\dot{x} - 6x \\, = \\, -6x -5y.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      In matrix form, this is [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = A \\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]A = \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\\\\\ -6 & -5 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline]. (The matrix [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\\\\\ -6 & -5 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] arising this way is called the **companion matrix** of the polynomial [mathjaxinline]x^2+5x+6[/mathjaxinline].)  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Conversely, given a first-order system, one can eliminate function variables to find a higher-order ODE satisfied by one of the functions. But usually we just leave it as a system.  **Problem 10.2** Given that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2x - y[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 5x + 7y,[/mathjaxinline] |  |      eliminate [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] to find a 2nd order ODE involving only [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline].  ###  Solution  Solve for [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] in the first equation ([mathjaxinline]y=2x-\\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline]) and substitute into the second: [mathjax]2 \\dot{x} - \\ddot{x} = 5x + 7(2x-\\dot{x}).[/mathjax]|   ---|---   This simplifies to [mathjax]\\ddot{x} - 9 \\dot{x} + 19 x = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Similarly, we can make companion systems for higher order linear differential equations by introducing new function variables for the derivatives.  Given an [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] order homogeneous linear ODE  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D^nx+a_{n-1}\\left(D^{n-1} x\\right)+a_{n-2} \\left(D^{n-2} x\\right)+\\cdots +a_{1}\\left(Dx\\right) +a_0x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0,\\qquad \\text{where } D=\\frac{d}{dt},[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      define  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_{0}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.62)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle Dx_0 \\, =\\, Dx[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.63)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D x_1\\, =\\, D^2 x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.64)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\vdots[/mathjaxinline] |  |  | (4.65)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_{n-1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D x_{n-2} \\, =\\, D^{n-1}x.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.66)      Then the original order [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] DE can be rewritten as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D x_{n-1}=-a_{n-1}x_{n-1}-a_{n-2}x_{n-2}-\\cdots -a_{1}x_{1}-a_{0}x_{0}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Therefore, we have a system of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] first order equations: the definitions of [mathjaxinline]x_0,\\, \\cdots ,\\, x_{n-1},\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the original DE rewritten as above. In matrix form, the first order [mathjaxinline]n \\times n[/mathjaxinline] system is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\begin{pmatrix} x_0 \\\\\\ x_1 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ x_{n-2} \\\\\\ x_{n-1}\\end{pmatrix}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 0 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 1 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \\cdots & 1 \\\\\\ -a_{0} & -a_{1} & -a_{2} & \\cdots & -a_{n-1} \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} x_0 \\\\\\ x_1 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ x_{n-2} \\\\\\ x_{n-1}\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      The [mathjaxinline]n \\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix on the right hand side is called the **companion matrix,** and this [mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline] system is the **companion system** of the degree [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] ODE.    Note that the dimension of the companion system corresponds to the order of the single ODE we started with.  **Remark 10.3** The same procedure of converting to a first order system works even if the starting ODE is inhomogeneous:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D^nx+a_{n-1}\\left(D^{n-1} x\\right)+a_{n-2} \\left(D^{n-2} x\\right)+\\cdots +a_{1}\\left(Dx\\right) +a_0x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{orange}{b}} .[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      The resulting companion system will have an extra vector on the right hand side:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\begin{pmatrix} x_0 \\\\\\ x_1 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ x_{n-2} \\\\\\ x_{n-1}\\end{pmatrix}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 0 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 1 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \\cdots & 1 \\\\\\ -a_{0} & -a_{1} & -a_{2} & \\cdots & -a_{n-1} \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} x_0 \\\\\\ x_1 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ x_{n-2} \\\\\\ x_{n-1}\\end{pmatrix}+\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 0\\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ 0 \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{b}} \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      **Remark 10.4** For constant coefficient ODEs, the characteristic polynomial of the higher order ODE (scaled, if necessary, to have leading coefficient [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]) equals the characteristic polynomial of the matrix of the first-order system.  More generally, we can also convert higher-order **systems** of ODEs to first order systems. For example, a system of [mathjaxinline]4[/mathjaxinline] fifth order ODEs can be converted to a [mathjaxinline]20 \\times 20[/mathjaxinline] first order system ODEs. This is why it is enough to study first order systems.    Higher order ODEs vs. systems of ODEs", "filename": "05_homog-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Higher order ODEs vs. systems of ODEs"}

{"pageid": 170, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@sequential+block@partB03/block-v1:MITx+18.033x+1T2023+type@vertical+block@partB03-tab6", "text": "### Optimization problem  The optimal values of [mathjaxinline]k_{2}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b_{2}[/mathjaxinline] will minimize the maximum value of the black response curve. We have a plane of possible values for [mathjaxinline]k_{2}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b_{2}[/mathjaxinline] that we must attempt to minimize this problem over.  ![plane with x axis k2 and y axis b2](/static/images/tmd_paramspace_1.svg)  However, in our example where the building has a small damping constant, [mathjaxinline]b_{1}[/mathjaxinline], it can be shown that the parameters [mathjaxinline]k_{2}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b_{2}[/mathjaxinline] can be optimized independently of each other. Therefore, our approach is to fix [mathjaxinline]b_2 = 0.02[/mathjaxinline] and first determine the optimal value, [mathjaxinline]k_{2}^{*}[/mathjaxinline], of the spring constant.  ![A dotted horizontal line at b2 equals 0.02, a value along that line optimizes k2](/static/images/tmd_paramspace_2.svg)  Next we fix [mathjaxinline]k_{2} = k_{2}^{*}[/mathjaxinline] at this optimal value and determine the optimal value, [mathjaxinline]b_2^{*}[/mathjaxinline]. (You can test that if you then fix [mathjaxinline]b_2^*[/mathjaxinline], and try to re-optimize [mathjaxinline]k_2[/mathjaxinline], your answer does not change.)  ![A dotted vertical line at optimal k2 value, and the optimal value of b2 is found along that vertical line](/static/images/tmd_paramspace_3.svg)  Optimize values", "filename": "partB03-tab6-text2.html", "title": "Optimize values"}
